ews.com/society/jihadist-media-claims-two-more-maldivians-killed-in-syria-89915|title=Jihadist media claims two more Maldivians killed in Syria|accessdate=25 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006095438/http://minivannews.com/society/jihadist-media-claims-two-more-maldivians-killed-in-syria-89915|archivedate=6 October 2014}}</ref> 3 Chinese,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rightsidenews.com/2013042432414/world/terrorism/facebook-page-documents-foreigners-who-come-to-syria-from-western-countries-to-fight-the-regime.html |title=Facebook Page Documents Foreigners Who Come To Syria From Western Countries To Fight The Regime |publisher=Rightsidenews.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130817121008/http://www.rightsidenews.com/2013042432414/world/terrorism/facebook-page-documents-foreigners-who-come-to-syria-from-western-countries-to-fight-the-regime.html |archive-date=2013-08-17 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/02/05/us-mideast-crisis-china-idUSKBN0L90T620150205|title=Islamic State executes three of its Chinese militants: China paper|work=Reuters|date=5 February 2015|access-date=30 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924213135/http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/02/05/us-mideast-crisis-china-idUSKBN0L90T620150205|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> 3 Pakistanis,<ref name=\"shaghor\"/> 2\u20133 Filipinos,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/69817-dead-filipino-isis-jihadists|title=Filipino jihadists killed in Syria - reports|work=Rappler|accessdate=25 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140929164451/http://www.rappler.com/nation/69817-dead-filipino-isis-jihadists|archive-date=29 September 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> 2 Eritreans,<ref name=\"shaghor\">{{cite web|url=http://shaghor.com/index.php?s=26|title=Shaghor - Martyrs|accessdate=25 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006102726/http://shaghor.com/index.php?s=26|archivedate=6 October 2014}}</ref> 2 Mauritanians,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/security/01/09/moroccan-and-algerian-militants-fighting-alongside-al-qaeda-group-among-dead-in-syria.html |title=African Militants Killed in Syria Fighting Alongside al-Qaeda |publisher=Al-monitor.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921060443/http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/security/01/09/moroccan-and-algerian-militants-fighting-alongside-al-qaeda-group-among-dead-in-syria.html |archive-date=2013-09-21 |url-status=live }}</ref> 2 South Africans,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/2017/02/17/second-south-african-reportedly-killed-in-syria-while-rebels-wa/|title=Second South African Reportedly Killed In Syria, While Rebels Want To Swop SA Journalist For Captured Rebels|publisher=|accessdate=1 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170221185606/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/2017/02/17/second-south-african-reportedly-killed-in-syria-while-rebels-wa/|archive-date=21 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> 2 Spaniards,<ref name=\"tracking\">{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtoninstitute.org/policy-analysis/view/foreign-jihadists-in-syria-tracking-recruitment-networks|title=Foreign Jihadists in Syria: Tracking Recruitment Networks|publisher=|accessdate=25 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141009045841/https://www.washingtoninstitute.org/policy-analysis/view/foreign-jihadists-in-syria-tracking-recruitment-networks|archive-date=9 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> 2 Uzbeks,<ref name=\"shuhadanationality\"/><ref name=\"onebulgarian\"/> 1 Armenian,<ref name=\"shaghor\"/> 1 Bulgarian,<ref name=\"onebulgarian\">{{cite web |url=http://paper.standartnews.com/en/article.php?d=2013-06-06&article=43126 |title=One Bulgarian among 280 Foreign Fighters Killed in Syria |publisher=Paper.standartnews.com |accessdate=2013-08-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055053/http://paper.standartnews.com/en/article.php?d=2013-06-06&article=43126 |archive-date=2013-09-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref> 1 Chadian,<ref name=\"names\"/> 1 Japanese,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/world-news/live-haruna-yukawa-isis-beheading-5035736|title=Haruna Yukawa ISIS beheading: Recap after terror group 'executes Japanese hostage'|author=Anthony Bond|date=24 January 2015|work=mirror|access-date=5 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180515044133/https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/world-news/live-haruna-yukawa-isis-beheading-5035736|archive-date=15 May 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> 1 Kazakh,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=72782|title=The airdrop in Beqres east of Deir Ezzor arrests a European explosive expert and Arab fighter and kills a Kazakh fighter and his family|publisher=|accessdate=5 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170902111254/http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=72782|archive-date=2 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> 1 Romanian<ref name=\"tracking\"/> and 1 Slovenian.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/08/03/middleeast/uk-syria-death-kurdish/index.html|title=British national dies fighting ISIS in Syria|first=Angela |last=Dewan|publisher=CNN|accessdate=1 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808073355/http://www.cnn.com/2016/08/03/middleeast/uk-syria-death-kurdish/index.html|archive-date=8 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign soldiers killed===\n\n469\u2013547 foreign soldiers have been killed during the conflict, mostly in the border areas with Syria.\n\n{{flagicon|Iraq}} '''16 servicemen killed'''<br />On 2 March 2013, one Iraqi soldier was killed during clashes between Syrian rebels and government forces at a Syrian-Iraqi border crossing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.naharnet.com/stories/en/74130-iraqi-soldier-killed-by-fire-from-syria |title=Iraqi Soldier Killed by Fire from Syria |publisher=Naharnet.com |date=2013-03-03 |accessdate=2013-08-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130801024121/http://www.naharnet.com/stories/en/74130-iraqi-soldier-killed-by-fire-from-syria |archive-date=2013-08-01 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 4 March 2013, 13 Iraqi soldiers were killed by unknown gunmen near the border with Syria while they were transporting 65 Syrian soldiers and government officials back to their country after they had retreated to Iraq a few days earlier. 48 of the Syrians were also killed in the attack.<ref>{{cite news |last=Yacoub |first=Khaled |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/03/04/us-syria-crisis-idUSBRE9230S620130304 |title=At least 40 Syrian soldiers killed going home in Iraq |publisher=Reuters.com |date=2013-03-04 |accessdate=2013-08-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131015041743/http://www.reuters.com/article/2013/03/04/us-syria-crisis-idUSBRE9230S620130304 |archive-date=2013-10-15 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Donnelly |first=Thomas |url=http://washingtonexaminer.com/syrian-jets-bomb-northern-city-overrun-by-rebels/article/2523370 |title=Syrian jets bomb northern city overrun by rebels |publisher=Washingtonexaminer.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928053739/http://washingtonexaminer.com/syrian-jets-bomb-northern-city-overrun-by-rebels/article/2523370 |archive-date=2013-09-28 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 9 June 2013, Syrian rebels attacked a southern Iraqi border post, killing one Iraqi guard and wounding two.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/world/syria-rebels-fire-on-iraq/703066.html |title=Syria rebels fire on Iraq border posts, one killed |publisher=Channelnewsasia.com |date=2013-06-09 |accessdate=2013-08-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615180738/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/world/syria-rebels-fire-on-iraq/703066.html |archive-date=2013-06-15 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 14 July 2013, another attack by fighters from the Syrian side of the border left one Iraqi policeman dead and five others wounded.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail/2013/07/13/313673/syria-militants-kill-iraqi-border-guard/ |title=Iraqi border guard killed in Syria violence spillover |publisher=Presstv.ir |date=2013-07-13 |accessdate=2013-08-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130820235522/http://www.presstv.ir/detail/2013/07/13/313673/syria-militants-kill-iraqi-border-guard/ |archive-date=2013-08-20 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jordan}} '''8 servicemen killed'''<br /> A Jordanian soldier was killed in clashes with armed militants who were attempting to cross the border from Jordan into Syria on 22 October 2012.<ref>{{cite web |author=BARBARA SURK Associated Press |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/breaking-news/ci_21826861/jordanian-soldier-killed-clash-at-syrian-border |title=Syrian violence spills into Jordan, Lebanon |publisher=Mercurynews.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131003032056/http://www.mercurynews.com/breaking-news/ci_21826861/jordanian-soldier-killed-clash-at-syrian-border |archive-date=2013-10-03 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 3 January 2015, ISIL burned a Jordanian military pilot alive in a metal cage. The pilot was captured after his airplane crashed near [[Raqqa]] while conducting air-strikes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-31129416|title=Jordan pilot murder: Islamic State deploys asymmetry of fear|date=4 February 2015|publisher=|accessdate=1 April 2017|via=www.bbc.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170409045100/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-31129416|archive-date=9 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Six Jordanian soldiers were killed by a car-bomb blast near the Syrian refugee camp of al-Rukban on 21 June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/06/jordan-soldiers-killed-syria-border-bomb-attack-160621064610938.html|title=Jordan soldiers killed in Syria border bomb attack|publisher=|accessdate=1 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170512031654/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/06/jordan-soldiers-killed-syria-border-bomb-attack-160621064610938.html|archive-date=12 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Lebanon}} '''60 servicemen killed'''<br /> On 1 February 2013, two Lebanese soldiers were killed, along with 1-2 militants, and six were wounded in clashes near the Syrian border which started after an attempt by the military to arrest an anti-Assad rebel commander, who was also killed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Politics/2013/Feb-02/204737-arsal-ambush-kills-two-lebanese-soldiers-hunting-w.ashx |title=Arsal ambush kills two Lebanese soldiers hunting wanted fugitive |publisher=Dailystar.com.lb |date= |accessdate=2013-08-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014225632/http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Politics/2013/Feb-02/204737-arsal-ambush-kills-two-lebanese-soldiers-hunting-w.ashx |archive-date=2013-10-14 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/02/world/middleeast/syria-crisis.html|title=Soldiers in Lebanon Die in Raid Near Syria|date=2 February 2013|work=The New York Times|accessdate=12 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414173221/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/02/world/middleeast/syria-crisis.html|archive-date=14 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Local-News/2013/Feb-01/204650-army-patrol-ambushed-in-east-lebanon-several-casua.ashx#axzz2JfNXn2Mh |title=Four soldiers killed in east Lebanon ambush |publisher=Dailystar.com.lb |date=2013-02-01 |accessdate=2013-08-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190223131443/http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Local-News/2013/Feb-01/204650-army-patrol-ambushed-in-east-lebanon-several-casua.ashx#axzz2JfNXn2Mh |archive-date=2019-02-23 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 28 May 2013, three Lebanese soldiers were killed in an attack on their checkpoint near the border town of Arsal by unknown militants who then fled over the border into Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/29/world/middleeast/syria.html|title=Rocket and Gun Attacks Add to Fears That Syria\u2019s Strife Is Reaching Lebanon|date=29 May 2013|work=The New York Times|accessdate=12 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001033928/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/29/world/middleeast/syria.html|archive-date=1 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> On 29 March 2014, three soldiers were killed and four wounded in a suicide bomb attack on their checkpoint near Arsal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2014/03/30/suicide-bombing-lebanon-kills-three|title=Suicide bombing in Lebanon kills three|work=News|accessdate=25 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025114626/http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2014/03/30/suicide-bombing-lebanon-kills-three|archive-date=25 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> 20 soldiers were killed during the [[Battle of Arsal (2014)|Battle of Arsal]] against Syrian and other foreign jihadists and a further 13 were captured and subsequently executed. On 19 September, two soldiers were killed by a roadside bomb near Arsal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trust.org/item/20140919193813-jois9|title=Syria militants kill captive Lebanese soldier, bomb kills two|author=Thomson Reuters Foundation|publisher=|accessdate=25 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112003918/http://www.trust.org/item/20140919193813-jois9/|archive-date=12 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> On 2 December, six soldiers were killed and one wounded in an ambush by unknown gunmen in the Tal Hamra area of Ras Baalbek, near the border with Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2014/12/lebanese-troops-killed-near-syrian-border-2014122193646646562.html|title=Lebanese troops killed near Syrian border|work=aljazeera.com|access-date=2014-12-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141209081541/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2014/12/lebanese-troops-killed-near-syrian-border-2014122193646646562.html|archive-date=2014-12-09|url-status=live}}</ref> On 23 January 2015, eight soldiers were killed and 22 wounded near Ras Baalbek after their outpost near the border was attacked by ISIL. The fighting also left more than 40 militants dead.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2015/Jan-24/285195-lebanon-army-finds-3-more-bodies-of-soldiers-as-guns-fall-silent.ashx|title=8 soldiers dead, 22 wounded as Lebanon border battle ends|work=The Daily Star Newspaper - Lebanon|access-date=2015-01-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128064234/http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2015/Jan-24/285195-lebanon-army-finds-3-more-bodies-of-soldiers-as-guns-fall-silent.ashx|archive-date=2015-01-28|url-status=live}}</ref> Three soldiers were also killed during [[Qalamoun offensive (July\u2013August 2017)|an offensive against ISIL]] in the border area in August 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-lebanon-syria/three-lebanese-soldiers-killed-in-landmine-along-border-with-syria-security-source-idUSKCN1B00G9|title=Three Lebanese soldiers killed in landmine on Syria border: security source|date=20 August 2017|publisher=|via=Reuters|access-date=16 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903080953/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-lebanon-syria/three-lebanese-soldiers-killed-in-landmine-along-border-with-syria-security-source-idUSKCN1B00G9|archive-date=3 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Russia}} '''133\u2013156 servicemen killed'''\n{{See also|Russian Armed Forces casualties in Syria}}\n\nFollowing the start of [[Russian military intervention in Syria|Russia's intervention in Syria]] against rebel and ISIL forces at the end of September 2015, 116 soldiers had died by 23 February 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://eaworldview.com/2019/03/syria-daily-russia-acknowledges-deaths-of-3-troops/ |title=Syria Daily: Russia Acknowledges Deaths of 3 Troops |access-date=2019-11-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330073541/https://eaworldview.com/2019/03/syria-daily-russia-acknowledges-deaths-of-3-troops/ |archive-date=2019-03-30 |url-status=live }}</ref> Among them, was a Russian military co-pilot who was killed when his Su-24 military plane was shot down near the Turkish-Syrian border by the Turkish military on 24 November 2015. His pilot was later recovered alive and well by Russian and Syrian special forces. Additionally, a Russian marine was killed when his military rescue helicopter was shot down by rebels while searching for the downed plane's pilots.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-says-marine-killed-during-mission-to-find-downed-pilots-1448391549|title=Russia Says Marine Killed During Mission to Find Downed Pilots|author=Thomas Grove|date=24 November 2015|work=WSJ|accessdate=12 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160410015352/http://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-says-marine-killed-during-mission-to-find-downed-pilots-1448391549|archive-date=10 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Almost half of the deaths were attributed to the crash of an [[An-26]] on approach to Khmeimim air base in Latakia, and the accidental shooting down of a reconnaissance plane by Syrian air-defenses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tass.com/defense/1023714|title=Russia lost 112 servicemen over three years of counter-terror operation in Syria - MP|website=TASS|accessdate=19 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190212015832/http://tass.com/defense/1023714|archive-date=12 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Between 15 and 18 January 2020, 4 Russian soldiers were killed by jihadist groups in the eastern countryside of Idlib.<ref>http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=153207</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Turkey}} '''241\u2013296 servicemen killed'''\n{{See also|Turkish Armed Forces casualties in Syria}}\nTwo members of the Turkish Air Force were killed when their F-4 Phantom II military jet was shot down near the Turkish-Syrian border by the Syrian Army on 22 June 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2012/07/201274122120638820.html |title=Turkey locates bodies of downed jet pilots |publisher=Aljazeera.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010173817/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2012/07/201274122120638820.html |archive-date=2017-10-10 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 2 May 2013, one Turkish border guard policeman was killed in a clash with smugglers or rebel fighters on the border between Turkey and Syria. According to the opposition, two rebels were killed as well.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldbulletin.net/?aType=haber&ArticleID=107960 |title=Turkish police killed in clashes on Syrian border |publisher=Worldbulletin.net |date=2013-05-02 |accessdate=2013-08-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130915234625/http://www.worldbulletin.net/?aType=haber&ArticleID=107960 |archive-date=2013-09-15 |url-status=live }}</ref> Throughout 2014, seven soldiers and a policeman were killed along the border with Syria in shootouts with foreign jihadists, Kurdish fighters and other unknown gunmen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailysabah.com/nation/2014/03/25/isil-connection-in-attack-against-turkish-security-forces|title=ISIL CONNECTION IN ATTACK AGAINST TURKISH SECURITY FORCES|work=dailysabah.com|accessdate=25 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160313005134/http://www.dailysabah.com/nation/2014/03/25/isil-connection-in-attack-against-turkish-security-forces|archive-date=13 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-soldier-killed-in-syria-border-clash-with-smugglers-official.aspx?pageID=238&nID=69440&NewsCatID=509|title=Third Turkish soldier dies after deadly clashes with militants on Syrian border|publisher=|accessdate=26 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224183330/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-soldier-killed-in-syria-border-clash-with-smugglers-official.aspx?pageID=238&nID=69440&NewsCatID=509|archive-date=24 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2014/12/turkish-soldiers-killed-syria-border-201412954440122185.html|title=Turkish soldier kills comrades and himself|work=aljazeera.com|access-date=2014-12-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403140058/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2014/12/turkish-soldiers-killed-syria-border-201412954440122185.html|archive-date=2015-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref> On 22 February 2015, a soldier was killed in an accident during a military incursion into Syria to evacuate Turkish troops at the [[Tomb of Suleyman Shah]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/wires/afp/article-2963690/Turkey-evacuates-troops-guarding-tomb-inside-Syria-PM.html|title=Turkish troops enter Syria to relocate historic tomb|work=Mail Online|location=London|date=22 February 2015|access-date=22 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150222173830/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/wires/afp/article-2963690/Turkey-evacuates-troops-guarding-tomb-inside-Syria-PM.html|archive-date=22 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Later, in two incidents in July and September, two soldiers were killed and five wounded by cross-border fire from ISIL territory in Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/24/world/europe/turkey-isis-us-airstrikes-syria.html|title=U.S. Jets to Use Turkish Bases in War on ISIS|date=24 July 2015|work=The New York Times|accessdate=12 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160708164824/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/24/world/europe/turkey-isis-us-airstrikes-syria.html|archive-date=8 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2015/09/01/Turkish-soldier-killed-in-cross-border-fire-from-ISIS-territory-in-Syria-.html|title=Turkish soldier killed in cross-border fire from ISIS territory in Syria|publisher=|access-date=2016-02-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331181500/https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2015/09/01/Turkish-soldier-killed-in-cross-border-fire-from-ISIS-territory-in-Syria-.html|archive-date=2019-03-31|url-status=live}}</ref> On 15 February 2016, a soldier died at the border during clashes against human smugglers that tried to cross the border illegally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-soldier-killed-in-intervention-against-human-smugglers-at-syrian-border.aspx?pageID=238&nID=95187&NewsCatID=352|title=Turkish soldier killed in intervention against human smugglers at Syrian border - MIDEAST|publisher=|accessdate=12 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160302123604/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-soldier-killed-in-intervention-against-human-smugglers-at-syrian-border.aspx?pageID=238&nID=95187&NewsCatID=352|archive-date=2 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Two Turkish soldiers died in a suicide bombing at a Syrian border crossing in mid-August.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-syria-turkey-idUSKCN10P0SE|title=Islamic State says bus blast killed 50 fighters at Syria-Turkey crossing|date=15 August 2017|publisher=|accessdate=1 April 2017|via=Reuters|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307185531/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-syria-turkey-idUSKCN10P0SE|archive-date=7 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the start of [[Operation Euphrates Shield|Turkey's ground incursion into Syria]] against ISIL and Kurdish forces in late August 2016, 72 soldiers had died by 29 March 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haberler.com/firat-kalkani-nda-sehit-olan-72-askerin-anisina-10477562-haberi/|title=F\u0131rat Kalkan\u0131'nda \u015eehit Olan 72 Askerin An\u0131s\u0131na, Afrin'e 72 U\u00e7akla Sald\u0131r\u0131 D\u00fczenlendi}}</ref> 61\u201396 more died as result of Turkey's [[Operation Olive Branch|second large incursion]] between 2018 and 2019,<ref>54 killed (20 Jan.\u20136 July 2018),[https://www.aa.com.tr/en/turkey/turkey-neutralizes-over-4-500-terrorists-in-afrin-army/1196627] 1 killed (13 Dec. 2018),[https://www.france24.com/en/20181213-syria-afrin-turkish-soldier-killed-kurdish-militia-ypg] 1 killed (18 Feb. 2019),[https://www.dailysabah.com/war-on-terror/2019/02/18/1-turkish-soldier-killed-during-anti-terror-op-in-northern-syria/amp] 1 killed (31 March 2019),[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-syria-turkey/one-turkish-soldier-killed-in-syria-military-retaliates-ministry-idUSKCN1RC0HR] 1 killed (4 May 2019),[https://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/one-soldier-killed-another-wounded-in-syria-143157] 1 killed (26 June 2019),[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-turkey/turkish-soldier-killed-in-clashes-with-kurdish-militants-in-syria-ministry-idUSKCN1TR113] 2 killed (11 Oct. 2019),[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-turkey-attacks/two-turkish-soldiers-killed-in-kurdish-militant-attack-in-syria-ministry-idUSKBN1WQ26W] total of 61 reported killed</ref><ref>93 killed (20 Jan. 2018\u201326 June 2019),[http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=132599] 1 killed (5 Aug. 2019),[http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=136684] 2 killed (11 Oct. 2019),[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-turkey-attacks/two-turkish-soldiers-killed-in-kurdish-militant-attack-in-syria-ministry-idUSKBN1WQ26W] total of 96 reported killed</ref> and 64\u201378 were killed in Idlib during the [[Turkish military operation in Idlib Governorate|Turkish military operation that begun in February 2018]].<ref>1 killed (6 Feb. 2018),[http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/turkish-soldier-killed-syrias-idlib-509393796] 1 killed (6 April 2019),[https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/turkish-soldier-killed-in-northern-latakia-after-unknown-group-opens-fire-near-border-crossing/] 1 killed (28 June 2019),[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/06/turkish-soldier-dies-attack-military-post-syria-idlib-190628055001892.html] 57 killed (3 Feb.-5 March 2020; per Turkish President),[https://www.sozcu.com.tr/2020/gundem/erdogan-idlibde-59-sehit-verdik-5667724/][https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/turkey-to-keep-military-observation-posts-in-idlib-syria/1724137] 72 killed (3 Feb.-5 March 2020; per SOHR),[http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=156424][http://www.syriahr.com/?p=367235][http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=154347] 3 killed (18-19 March 2020),[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-turkey/turkish-soldier-killed-in-syrias-idlib-governors-office-idUSKBN2162K3] total of 64\u201378 killed</ref><ref group=note>Presented Turkish losses during the operation in Idlib Governorate do not include unconfirmed claims of 50\u2013100 dead in the February 2020 [[2020 Balyun airstrikes|Balyun airstrikes]].[https://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/idlib-tuerkische-soldaten-sterben-durch-luftangriffe-in-syrien-a-f42bf8b4-e061-4a7c-a697-7fc97fe37c3a][https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2020/02/turkey-syria-russia-deciphering-attack-on-turkish-troops.html][https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/dozens-of-turkish-soldiers-killed-in-strike-in-idlib-in-syria/ar-BB10uvmc?li=BBnb7Kz][https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/mar/02/erdogan-turkey-syria-assad?] Instead, they include 33 soldiers killed in the airstrike confirmed by Turkey.[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-turkey-military-attack/attack-in-syrias-idlib-killed-33-turkish-soldiers-hatay-governor-idUSKCN20M030]</ref> One soldier also died in March 2019, in the area of Operation Euphrates Shield.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/war-on-terror/2019/03/15/turkish-soldier-killed-during-operations-in-northern-syria |title=Turkish soldier killed during operations in northern Syria |access-date=2019-04-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190408124825/https://www.dailysabah.com/war-on-terror/2019/03/15/turkish-soldier-killed-during-operations-in-northern-syria |archive-date=2019-04-08 |url-status=live }}</ref> Another 16 Turkish soldiers died during [[2019 Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria|Turkey's third incursion]] in clashes against the SDF.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/tr/baris-pinari-harekati/bakan-akar-yasaklanan-hicbir-muhimmati-veya-kimyasal-silahi-kullanmadik/1651521|title=Bakan Akar: Yasaklanan hi\u00e7bir m\u00fchimmat\u0131 veya kimyasal silah\u0131 kullanmad\u0131k|website=aa.com.tr}}<br />[http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-soldier-killed-by-accident-in-n-syria-149072 Turkish soldier killed by accident in N Syria]<br />[https://www.dailysabah.com/war-on-terror/2019/11/28/2-soldiers-killed-in-ypg-attack-in-se-turkey 2 soldiers killed in YPG attack in SE Turkey]<br />[https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/2-turkish-soldiers-martyred-in-terrorist-attacks/1661823 2 Turkish soldiers martyred in terrorist attacks]</ref> During January 2020, between seven and ten Turkish soldiers were killed in two car bombings near [[Ras al-Ayn]] and in northern Raqqa,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1610276/middle-east|title=Four Turkish soldiers killed in car bombing in Syria|website=Arab News|date=8 January 2020}}</ref><ref>[http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=152556 Ras Al-Ain bomb attacks cause the highest daily death toll ever among Turkish soldiers]</ref><ref>[http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=153093 Three Turkish soldiers among ten killed in car-bomb explosion north of Raqqa]</ref> while one or four more died in two bombings near Ras al-Ayn in March.<ref>[https://ahvalnews.com/ras-al-ayn/turkish-soldier-three-locals-killed-ras-al-ayn-bombing Turkish soldier, three locals killed in Ras al Ayn bombing]<br>[http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=157185 Four explosions hit areas in Ras al-Ain countryside leaves eight people dead, including Turkish soldiers]</ref> One soldier was also killed in an accident in the area of Operation Peace Spring in February 2020,<ref>[https://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/suriyede-kazada-sehit-olan-uzman-onbasi-ceyhun-tas-memleketine-ugurlandi-41443140 Suriye\u2019de kazada \u015fehit olan Uzman Onba\u015f\u0131 Ceyhun Ta\u015f, memleketine u\u011furland\u0131]</ref> and one committed suicide in the area in March 2020.<ref>[https://hawarnews.com/en/haber/for-refusing-to-stay-in-serkaniy-turkish-soldier-committed-suicide-h15491.html For refusing to stay in Ser\u00eakaniy\u00ea, Turkish soldier committed suicide]</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|France}} '''1 serviceman killed''' <br /> The [[\u00c9lys\u00e9e Palace]] announced in September 2017 that a French servicemen of the 13th regiment of paratroopers died in the Levant region during Operation Chammal. It was not known where the precise location of the soldier's death.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20170923-french-soldier-killed-iraq-syria-military-zone|title=French soldier killed in Iraq-Syria military zone, \u00c9lys\u00e9e Palace says|date=23 September 2017|website=France 24|accessdate=19 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190224175919/https://www.france24.com/en/20170923-french-soldier-killed-iraq-syria-military-zone|archive-date=24 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|United Kingdom}} '''1 serviceman killed''' <br />A British soldier, named as Sgt Matt Tunroe of the 3rd Battalion the Parachute Regiment died on 30 March 2018 in [[Manbij|Manbij.]] This was initially reported as an IED explosion from which a U.S. soldier had also been killed from.<ref name=\"cnn.com\">{{cite web|title=US and British troops killed in Syria blast|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/03/30/politics/syria-coalition-ied/index.html|access-date=2018-04-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180331104211/https://www.cnn.com/2018/03/30/politics/syria-coalition-ied/index.html|archive-date=2018-03-31|url-status=live}}</ref> However, the Ministry of Defence later clarified it was a case of [[friendly fire]], caused by the accidental detonation of explosives carried by another coalition soldier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2019-07-27/british-soldier-sergeant-matt-tonroe-killed-by-friendly-fire-not-roadside-bomb-investigation-finds/|title=British soldier Sergeant Matt Tonroe killed by friendly fire not roadside bomb, investigation finds|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|United States}} '''9 servicemen killed'''<br /> A U.S. pilot was killed on 30 November 2014, when his [[General Dynamics F-16 Fighting Falcon|F-16]] fighter aircraft crashed in Jordan following a combat mission against the Islamic State jihadist group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f-16.net/f-16-news-article4910.html|title=Pilot killed as U.S. F-16 crashes in Jordan|publisher=|access-date=2018-07-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707230817/http://www.f-16.net/f-16-news-article4910.html|archive-date=2018-07-07|url-status=live}}</ref> Also, a U.S. special forces member died due to a bomb explosion while supporting Kurdish-led forces during the ''[[Raqqa campaign (2016\u20132017)|Wrath of Euphrates]]'' offensive against ISIL-held [[Raqqa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2016/11/25/US-service-member-killed-in-blast-in-Syria-.html|title=US service member killed in blast in Syria|publisher=|access-date=2016-11-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180710040931/http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2016/11/25/US-service-member-killed-in-blast-in-Syria-.html|archive-date=2018-07-10|url-status=live}}</ref> Two other service members died due to non-combat causes in northern Syria in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/us-service-member-killed-accident-syria/story?id=47658836|title=US service member killed in Syria identified as 22-year-old from Georgia|first=A. B. C.|last=News|date=27 May 2017|website=ABC News|access-date=26 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170526140904/http://abcnews.go.com/International/us-service-member-killed-accident-syria/story?id=47658836|archive-date=26 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> A US servicemen died on 30 March 2018 by an IED explosion in Manbij.<ref name=\"cnn.com\"/> Four Americans, including two soldiers, were killed by a bombing in Manbij city on 16 January 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/american-service-members-killed-bomb-blast-northern-syria/story?id=60444620|title=3 of the Americans killed in bomb blast in northern Syria identified|website=ABC News|accessdate=19 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220232117/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/american-service-members-killed-bomb-blast-northern-syria/story?id=60444620|archive-date=20 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/16/politics/syria-attack-us-patrolled-city/index.html|title=4 Americans killed in Syria attack. ISIS claims responsibility|author1=Zachary Cohen|author2=Veronica Stracqualursi|author3=Kevin Liptak|website=CNN|accessdate=19 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416172831/https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/16/politics/syria-attack-us-patrolled-city/index.html|archive-date=16 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> One American soldier was killed on 28 April 2019,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wxyz.com/news/army-private-from-southwest-detroit-dies-in-syria-in-non-combat-incident |title=Army private from southwest Detroit dies in Syria in non-combat incident |access-date=2019-05-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506131337/https://www.wxyz.com/news/army-private-from-southwest-detroit-dies-in-syria-in-non-combat-incident |archive-date=2019-05-06 |url-status=live }}</ref> possibly due to Turkish shelling.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=126569 |title=Mystery surrounds the killing of a US soldier in the countryside of Ayn al-Arab (Kobani) amid accusations against Turkey of targeting him |access-date=2019-05-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190505164800/http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=126569 |archive-date=2019-05-05 |url-status=live }}</ref> Another US soldier died in Syria on January 24, 2020, following a rollover crash in Deir ez-Zor province.<ref>[https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2020/jan/25/army-identifies-antonio-moore-soldier-killed-syria/ Army identifies U.S. soldier killed in Syria]</ref>\n\n==Foreign air-strike casualties==\nThe SOHR considers the following figures on ISIL, al-Nusra and other rebel fatalities to be higher due to the groups' efforts to hide their losses.\n\n===[[American-led intervention in the Syrian Civil War|American-led intervention]]===\n\nAccording to SOHR, U.S.-led Coalition airstrikes have killed 14,024 people across Syria, of which: 9,170 dead were ISIL fighters, 360 Al-Nusra Front militants and other rebels, 169 government soldiers and 3,835 civilians. The air strikes occurred in the period between 23 September 2014 and 15 March 2020.<ref name=SOHR/>\n\n===[[Russian military intervention in the Syrian Civil War|Russian intervention]]===\nAccording to SOHR, Russian airstrikes in Syria killed about 19,900 people, of whom 5,244 were ISIL fighters, 6,054 militants from the Al-Qaeda affiliate al-Nusra Front and other rebel forces, 8,622 civilians and five Turkish soldiers. The air strikes occurred in the period between 30 September 2015 and 29 February 2020.<ref name=\"russianair\">{{cite web|url=http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=156076|title=8,622 civilians among nearly 20,000 persons killed by Russian jets since the start of Russia\u2019s military operation in Syria|work=SOHR|date=February 29, 2020|accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/russian-bombing-mistake-kills-three-turkish-soldiers-in-syria-20170210-gu9r5d.html |title=Russian bombing mistake kills three Turkish soldiers in Syria |access-date=2019-06-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190601102458/https://www.smh.com.au/world/russian-bombing-mistake-kills-three-turkish-soldiers-in-syria-20170210-gu9r5d.html |archive-date=2019-06-01 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=155503&__cf_chl_jschl_tk__=7c46b3e6934bc2dd742fc1e8b62bb0d57d8e6ed5-1582320782-0-AXfGWJ7C7W4IxU3BKbjbv0dI3GVmnpucDOvRwlH5V4Z35UNFweIYYoZZODH8x-Xj3-X621fDvEUfBC64mD3-lap0fcnSW6f_IljyF4iL2vRtVbjAqJxdIGXv0ZLSgLVzlaqrXTN66dVe-Wyzv76FHxd6K6ldPaH971bwee_NxnCLWF-l6o2uInxUbGCbN8x2CBu_7aKxijk_mrcFZMkCrhFQKGcCzB-uw8zD2xjgH_GeSqVl3LWIABnAtbj236qdYqUpQeSe9afK9n0q_YzqqxnwyjETov0RQ7lT4pD90DT7</ref> The ''New York Times'' accused the Russian air force of specifically focusing on attacking civilian hospitals and other medical facilities, including hospitals on so-called \"deconfliction list\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/13/world/middleeast/russia-bombing-syrian-hospitals.html|title=12 Hours. 4 Syrian Hospitals Bombed. One Culprit: Russia.|last=Hill|first=Evan|date=2019-10-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-10-13|last2=Triebert|first2=Christiaan|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013071012/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/13/world/middleeast/russia-bombing-syrian-hospitals.html|archive-date=2019-10-13|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Airwars, a not-for-profit transparency project aimed both at tracking and archiving international military actions in conflict zones such as Iraq, Syria and Libya, Russian airstrikes have killed 3,736\u20135,510 civilians <ref>{{cite web|url=https://airwars.org/conflict/russian-military-in-syria/|title=Reported civilian deaths from Russian military strikes in Syria|access-date=2019-10-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190524182735/https://airwars.org/conflict/russian-military-in-syria/|archive-date=2019-05-24|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://airwars.org/about/team/|title=Airwars: About Us|access-date=2019-10-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426235526/https://airwars.org/about/team/|archive-date=2019-04-26|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the Russian Defense Ministry, since the start of Russia's aerial campaign in Syria and by 20 October 2018, the Russian Air Force killed more than 87,500 rebels and ISIL fighters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/world/2018-10-20-russia-says-88000-syria-rebels-killed/|title=Russia says 88,000 Syria rebels killed|first=|last=TimesLIVE|publisher=|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020113627/https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/world/2018-10-20-russia-says-88000-syria-rebels-killed/|archive-date=20 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Medical workers killed==\n{{Pie chart \n | caption=Killings of medical workers since the start of the Syrian Civil War, according to a [[Physicians for Human Rights|PHR]] summary<ref name=\"Medical_stats\">{{cite report |url= https://s3.amazonaws.com/PHR_Reports/doctors-in-the-crosshairs.pdf |last1= Baker |first1= Elise |last2= Brown |first2= Widney |title= Doctors in the Crosshairs: Four Years of Attacks on Health Care in Syria |publisher= Physicians for Human Rights |date= March 2015 |accessdate= 13 March 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150317193410/https://s3.amazonaws.com/PHR_Reports/doctors-in-the-crosshairs.pdf |archivedate= 17 March 2015 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n | other = \n | label1 = Attacks by government forces\n | value1 = 95.5 | color1 = Red\n | label2 = ISIL or rebel groups\n | value2 = 2.5 | color2 = Grey\n | label3 = Kurdish forces\n | value3 = 0.1 | color3 = Blue\n | label4 = Unknown forces\n | value4 = 1.9 | color4 = Black\n }}\n\nA February 2015 joint report by the Center for Public Health and Human Rights of the Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health and the Syrian American Medical Society asserted that \"Syria is the most dangerous place in the world to be a doctor\".<ref>{{Cite report |author=  |authorlink=  |date= February 2015 |title= Syrian Medical Voices from the Ground: The Ordeal of Syria\u2019s Healthcare Professionals |url= http://media.nbcbayarea.com/documents/Syrian+Medical+Voices+from+the+Ground.pdf |publisher= The Center for Public Health and Human Rights of the Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health and the Syrian American Medical Society |page=  |docket=  |asin=  |accessdate= 13 March 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150402115606/http://media.nbcbayarea.com/documents/Syrian+Medical+Voices+from+the+Ground.pdf |archivedate= 2 April 2015 |url-status= live }}</ref> Roughly half (an estimated 15,000)<ref name=JapanTimes_March2015/> of Syrian doctors fled the country.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.nbcchicago.com/news/local/Chicago-Doctors-Syrian-War-Hospital-295954681.html |title= Chicago Doctors Risk Arrest, Torture to Aid Dire Medical Care Void in Syria |last1= Leitner |first1= Tammy |last2= Capitanini |first2= Lisa |publisher= NBC Chicago |date= 12 April 2015 |accessdate= 13 March 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150402150834/http://www.nbcchicago.com/news/local/Chicago-Doctors-Syrian-War-Hospital-295954681.html |archive-date= 2 April 2015 |url-status= live }}</ref> The government passed a law in 2012 making it illegal to render medical aid to anyone suspected to be an opposition member and [[Amnesty International]] found that doctors and medical staff also took part in [[torture]] of patients.<ref name=JapanTimes_March2015/>\n\n[[Physicians for Human Rights]] has been tracking the medical personnel deaths in Syria, though they state that \"these numbers are conservative given the difficulties in reporting during a war.\" As of the end of September 2015, the number of medical workers killed in the Syrian civil war totaled 679.<ref>{{cite web|title=Anatomy of A Crisis: A Map of Attack on Health Care in Syria|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/PHR_syria_map/web/index.html|website=Physicians for Human Rights|accessdate=23 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151031030344/https://s3.amazonaws.com/PHR_syria_map/web/index.html|archive-date=31 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2017, the number of killed medical personnel was updated to more than 800. 723 of these deaths were attributable to the Syrian government, while 72 were killed by ISIL or rebel groups, one by Kurdish forces, and 13 by unidentified forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/wires/afp/article-4314462/Over-800-health-workers-killed-Syrian-war-crimes-report.html|title=Over 800 health workers killed in Syrian 'war crimes': report|work=AFP|accessdate=14 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315181901/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/wires/afp/article-4314462/Over-800-health-workers-killed-Syrian-war-crimes-report.html|archive-date=15 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res]] has reported that suppliers in Syria refuse to sell essential medical supplies such as gauze and surgical threads to doctors due to government intimidation, with this being a particular problem for besieged areas.<ref name=\"JapanTimes_March2015\">{{cite web | url= http://www.japantimes.co.jp/opinion/2015/03/20/commentary/world-commentary/doctors-being-targeted-in-syrias-brutal-war/#.VQwwHiPFLqD | last= Chelala | first= Cesar | title= Doctors being targeted in Syria\u2019s brutal war | publisher= The Japan Times | date= 20 March 2015 | accessdate= 20 March 2015 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150323213613/http://www.japantimes.co.jp/opinion/2015/03/20/commentary/world-commentary/doctors-being-targeted-in-syrias-brutal-war#.VQwwHiPFLqD | archive-date= 23 March 2015 | url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Casualties of the Iraq War]]\n*[[Casualty recording]]\n{{Portal|Asia|War}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Syrian civil war}}\n\n[[Category:War casualties by war]]\n[[Category:Syrian Civil War]]\n", "name_user": "Cengo-1992", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDeath tolls by time periods", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Casualties_of_the_Syrian_Civil_War"}
{"title_page": "Neal Ashkanasy", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Neal M. Ashkanasy\n| image       = Neal Ashkanasy taken 22 MAR 2019.jpg\n| caption     = Ashkanasy in 2019\n| birth_date  = {{birth-date and age|5 June 1945}}\n| birth_place = [[Melbourne, Australia]]\n| occupation  = Professor of Management\n| nationality = [[Australia]]n, [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse      = Linda Ashkanasy (married 1972)\n| children    = 3\n| known_for   = [[Emotions in the workplace]]\n| website     = {{URL|https://www.business.uq.edu.au/staff/neal-ashkanasy}}\n| awards      = Medal in the [[Order of Australia]] (OAM)<br> [[Elton Mayo]] award for excellence in teaching and research<br>Fellow of the [[Academy of the Social Sciences in Australia]]\n}}\n\n'''Neal M. Ashkanasy''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|OAM}} (born 5 June 1945) is an [[Australia]]n academic best known for his work on [[emotions in the workplace]].<ref name=\":1\" /> He was honored for his \"service to tertiary education, to psychology and to the community.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://statements.qld.gov.au/Statement/2017/1/26/premier-congratulates-queensland-honours-recipients|title=Premier congratulates Queensland Honours recipients|access-date=2017-03-26|language=en-AU|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312185647/http://statements.qld.gov.au/Statement/2017/1/26/premier-congratulates-queensland-honours-recipients|archive-date=12 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He began his career as a civil engineer but is now a Professor of Management at the [[University of Queensland]] Business School.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.business.uq.edu.au/staff/neal-ashkanasy|title=Neal Ashkanasy {{!}} UQ Business School|website=www.business.uq.edu.au|language=en|access-date=2017-03-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218000724/https://www.business.uq.edu.au/staff/neal-ashkanasy|archive-date=18 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education ==\nAshkanasy was born in [[Melbourne|Melbourne, Australia]] to [[Maurice Ashkanasy]], an early leader of the [[Australian Jews|Australian Jewish]] community, and Heather Helen Ashkanasy. He attended [[Mount Scopus Memorial College|Mt. Scopus College]] and [[Monash University]], where he completed a degree in [[Civil Engineering]] in 1966.  In 1968, he completed a master's degree in [[Hydraulic engineering|Water Engineering]] at the [[University of New South Wales]] in [[Sydney|Sydney, Australia]].<ref>Neal Ashkanasy - Who\u2019s who in Australia, 56 Ed., 2020, pp. 146-147. Melbourne, Australia: Information Australia. ISSN 08108228.</ref>\n\nAshkanasy returned to university in 1970, where he completed a Graduate Diploma in Computer Science and a Bachelor of Arts (major in psychology) with [[University Medal|First Class Honours and a University Meda]]<nowiki/>l, at the [[University of Queensland]] in Brisbane. He enrolled in a PhD in the UQ School of Psychology, which he completed in 1989.<ref>Neal Ashkanasy - Who\u2019s who in the management sciences, 2000, pp. 13-14. Cheltenham, UK: Edward Elgar. ISBN: 1840642378</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAshkanasy started work in [[Brisbane|Brisbane, Australia]] in 1968 with the Queensland Irrigation and Water Supply Commission and worked for the Commission (renamed the QWRC: the Queensland Water Resources Commission) for 18 years.  He began his career as a construction engineer on [[Fairbairn Dam]] in [[Central Queensland]], returning to the Brisbane Office of the QWRC in 1970, rising to the rank of Executive Engineer, Water Supply Investigations.  In this role, he oversaw hydrological investigations for the [[Wivenhoe Dam]] is on the [[Brisbane River]] in [[Australia]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/stop-playing-the-flood-blame-game/news-story/8724e48d6ab134afac077c80856e21a9|title=Stop playing the flood blame-game|access-date=2017-03-19}}</ref>  During that time, he was also actively involved in the [[Engineers Australia|Institution of Engineers, Australia]], eventually serving as Chair of its National Committee on Hydrology and Water Resources, during which time he oversaw production of the third edition of ''Australian Rainfall and Runoff''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://arr.ga.gov.au/|title=Australian Rainfall and Runoff - Australian Rainfall and Runoff|website=arr.ga.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2017-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226130338/http://arr.ga.gov.au/|archive-date=26 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Australian Rainfall and Runoff|last=Pilgrim|first=David H.|publisher=The Institution of Engineers, Australia|year=1987|isbn=085825-434-4|location=Barton, ACT. Australia|pages=vii}}</ref>  In 1975, he undertook a [[Winston Churchill Memorial Trusts|Churchill Fellowship]] world tour to study water resources development in the USA, Europe, Israel, and India.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.churchilltrust.com.au/fellows/?keywords=&year=1975|title=Fellows {{!}} Winston Churchill Memorial Trust|website=www.churchilltrust.com.au|access-date=2017-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324084116/https://www.churchilltrust.com.au/fellows/?keywords=&year=1975|archive-date=24 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCommencing his academic career in 1986 with the School of Psychology, Ashkanasy was later seconded to the UQ Technology and Innovation Management Centre (1989). In 1988, he was appointed a Lecturer (Assistant Professor) in the UQ School of Commerce, where he attained tenure and promotion in 1994 before moving to the (former) School of Management in 1995. In 2002, the schools of Commerce and Management merged to form the [[UQ Business School]]. From 2004\u20132008, he served as Associate Dean (Research) of the Faculty of Business, Economics, and Law.  His present position is Professor of Management in the [[UQ Business School]].<ref>Professor Neal Ashkanasy \u2013 UQ Researchers http://researchers.uq.edu.au. Retrieved 25 February, 2020</ref>\n\nAshkanasy is the founder of the \"Emonet\" (the Emotions network)<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.emotionsnet.org/|title=EMONET - Emotions Network|website=www.emotionsnet.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110411232330/http://www.emotionsnet.org/|archive-date=11 April 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> and \"Orgcult\" (Organizational Culture) [[Electronic mailing list|Listservs]], which are sponsored by the [[Academy of Management]].  The Emonet group sponsors the biannual \"International Conference on Emotions and Worklife\" which has been running since 1998.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.emotionsnet.org/sitemap/conferences/|title=Conferences {{!}} EMONET - Emotions Network|website=www.emotionsnet.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319195820/http://www.emotionsnet.org/sitemap/conferences/|archive-date=19 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The 10th \"Emonet Conference\" was held in [[Rome]] in July 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.emotionsnet.org/sitemap/conferences/emonet-x/|title=Emonet X {{!}} EMONET - Emotions Network|website=www.emotionsnet.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319195911/http://www.emotionsnet.org/sitemap/conferences/emonet-x/|archive-date=19 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\nAshkanasy has published over 300 journal articles and book chapters and is author or co-author of over 300 conference papers.  His research interests include emotions in the workplace, leadership and leader-member relations, organizational and national culture, and ethics in organizational behavior.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://researchers.uq.edu.au/researcher/319|title=Professor Neal Ashkanasy - UQ Researchers|website=researchers.uq.edu.au|access-date=2017-03-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313214510/http://researchers.uq.edu.au/researcher/319|archive-date=13 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Google Scholar]], his work has been cited more than 25,000 times.<ref>Neal M. Ashkanasy \u2013 Google Scholar Citations http://scholar.google.com. Retrieved on 04 March 2020.</ref>\n\nAshkanasy served from 2007 to 2014 as [[editor-in-chief]] of the ''[[Journal of Organizational Behavior]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Journal of Organizational Behavior |journal = Journal of Organizational Behavior|doi=10.1002/(ISSN)1099-1379 |citeseerx = 10.1.1.203.3751}}</ref> From 2004 to 2008, he was associate editor of the ''[[Academy of Management Learning and Education]]''. From 2011 to 2014, he served as associate editor of the ''[[Academy of Management Review]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://aom.org/Publications/AMR/Past-Editors-and-Associate-Editors.aspx |title=Past Editors and Associate Editors |website=aom.org |access-date=2017-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170321081847/http://aom.org/Publications/AMR/Past-Editors-and-Associate-Editors.aspx |archive-date=21 March 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> He is currently a member of the [[editorial board]] of ''[[Emotion Review]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://us.sagepub.com/en-us/nam/journal/emotion-review#editorial-board |title=Editorial Board |work=Emotion Review |publisher=[[SAGE Publications]] |accessdate=22 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324000504/https://us.sagepub.com/en-us/nam/journal/emotion-review#editorial-board |archive-date=24 March 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> (action editor) and [[book series]] editor of ''Research on Emotion in Organizations'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emeraldinsight.com/products/books/series.htm?id=1746-9791 |title=Research on Emotion in Organizations |publisher=[[Emerald Group Publishing]] |date=14 October 2011 |accessdate=22 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921064321/http://emeraldinsight.com/products/books/series.htm?id=1746-9791 |archive-date=21 September 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> published by [[Emerald Group Publishing]].\n\n==Awards and honours ==\nAshkanasy received a Medal of the [[Order of Australia]] (OAM) in 2017 \"for service to tertiary education, to psychology, and to the community\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.uq.edu.au/news/article/2017/01/uq-community-members-receive-australia-day-honours|title=UQ community members receive Australia Day honours|date=27 January 2017|publisher=University of Queensland|accessdate=11 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129201507/http://www.uq.edu.au/news/article/2017/01/uq-community-members-receive-australia-day-honours|archive-date=29 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n* Fellow of the [[Academy of Social Sciences]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.acss.org.uk/fellows/|title=Fellows - Academy of Social Sciences|work=Academy of Social Sciences|access-date=2017-03-23|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630101533/https://www.acss.org.uk/fellows/|archive-date=30 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Fellow of the [[Academy of the Social Sciences in Australia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.assa.edu.au/fellows/586/|title=Fellows Detail \u00bb ASSA|website=www.assa.edu.au|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324084749/http://www.assa.edu.au/fellows/586/|archive-date=24 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Fellow of the [[Society for Industrial and Organizational Psychology]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.siop.org/tip/backissues/July06/32fellows.aspx|title=Announcement of New SIOP Fellows July 2006|date=|publisher=Siop.org|accessdate=22 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314080843/http://www.siop.org/tip/backissues/July06/32fellows.aspx|archive-date=14 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Fellow of the [[Association for Psychological Science]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.psychologicalscience.org/fellows/fellows-new.cfm|title=Association for Psychological Science: APS Fellows|website=www.psychologicalscience.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170625182651/http://www.psychologicalscience.org/fellows/fellows-new.cfm|archive-date=25 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Life Fellow of the [[Australia and New Zealand Academy of Management]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.anzam.org/membership/membership-awards/|title=Life Fellow - Australian and New Zealand Academy of Management|work=Australian and New Zealand Academy of Management|access-date=2017-03-24|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324181126/https://www.anzam.org/membership/membership-awards/|archive-date=24 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[British Academy of Management|Fellow of the British Academy of Management]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bam.ac.uk/current-bam-fellows|title=Current BAM Fellows {{!}} bam.ac.uk|website=www.bam.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324175652/https://www.bam.ac.uk/current-bam-fellows|archive-date=24 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Fellow of the [[Southern Management Association]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.southernmanagement.org/default.asp?page=Fellows|title=SMA Fellows - Southern Management Association|website=www.southernmanagement.org|access-date=2017-03-24}}</ref>\n* Awarded the [[Elton Mayo]] award for excellence in teaching and research by the [[Australian Psychological Society]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://psychology.org.au/about/awards/elton_mayo/|title=Australian Psychological Society : Elton Mayo Awards|website=psychology.org.au|access-date=2017-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324175521/http://psychology.org.au/about/awards/elton_mayo/|archive-date=24 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Fellow of the Queensland Academy of Arts and Sciences (Council Member).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://qldacademy.org.au/academy-council/|title=Academy Council|work=Queensland Academy of Arts and Sciences|access-date=2017-03-24|language=en-AU|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324180032/http://qldacademy.org.au/academy-council/|archive-date=24 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Winston Churchill Memorial Trusts|Churchill Fellow]] in the field of water resource development.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.business.uq.edu.au/staff/neal-ashkanasy Official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ashkanasy, Neal}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Organizational psychologists]]\n[[Category:Australian business theorists]]\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Australian Jews]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Medal of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:Civil engineers]]\n[[Category:University of Queensland faculty]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Academy of the Social Sciences in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Neal M. Ashkanasy\n| image       = Neal Ashkanasy taken 22 MAR 2019.jpg\n| caption     = Ashkanasy in 2019\n| birth_date  = {{birth-date and age|5 June 1945}}\n| birth_place = [[Melbourne, Australia]]\n| occupation  = Professor of Management\n| nationality = [[Australia]]n, [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse      = Linda Ashkanasy (married 1972)\n| children    = 3\n| known_for   = [[Emotions in the workplace]]\n| website     = {{URL|https://www.business.uq.edu.au/staff/neal-ashkanasy}}\n| awards      = Medal in the [[Order of Australia]] (OAM)<br> [[Elton Mayo]] award for excellence in teaching and research<br>Fellow of the [[Academy of the Social Sciences in Australia]]\n}}\n\n'''Neal M. Ashkanasy''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|OAM}} (born 5 June 1945) is an [[Australia]]n academic best known for his work on [[emotions in the workplace]].<ref name=\":1\" /> He was honored for his \"service to tertiary education, to psychology and to the community.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://statements.qld.gov.au/Statement/2017/1/26/premier-congratulates-queensland-honours-recipients|title=Premier congratulates Queensland Honours recipients|access-date=2017-03-26|language=en-AU|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312185647/http://statements.qld.gov.au/Statement/2017/1/26/premier-congratulates-queensland-honours-recipients|archive-date=12 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He began his career as a civil engineer but is now a Professor of Management at the [[University of Queensland]] Business School.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.business.uq.edu.au/staff/neal-ashkanasy|title=Neal Ashkanasy {{!}} UQ Business School|website=www.business.uq.edu.au|language=en|access-date=2017-03-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218000724/https://www.business.uq.edu.au/staff/neal-ashkanasy|archive-date=18 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=January 2020}}\nAshkanasy was born in [[Melbourne|Melbourne, Australia]] to [[Maurice Ashkanasy]], an early leader of the [[Australian Jews|Australian Jewish]] community, and Heather Helen Ashkanasy. He attended [[Mount Scopus Memorial College|Mt. Scopus College]] and [[Monash University]], where he completed a degree in [[Civil Engineering]] in 1966.  In 1968, he completed a master's degree in [[Hydraulic engineering|Water Engineering]] at the [[University of New South Wales]] in [[Sydney|Sydney, Australia]].<ref>Neal Ashkanasy - Who\u2019s who in Australia, 56 Ed., 2020, pp. 146-147. Melbourne, Australia: Information Australia. ISSN 08108228.</ref>\n\nAshkanasy returned to university in 1970, where he completed a Graduate Diploma in Computer Science and a Bachelor of Arts (major in psychology) with [[University Medal|First Class Honours and a University Meda]]<nowiki/>l, at the [[University of Queensland]] in Brisbane. He enrolled in a PhD in the UQ School of Psychology, which he completed in 1989.<ref>Neal Ashkanasy - Who\u2019s who in the management sciences, 2000, pp. 13-14. Cheltenham, UK: Edward Elgar. ISBN: 1840642378</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAshkanasy started work in [[Brisbane|Brisbane, Australia]] in 1968 with the Queensland Irrigation and Water Supply Commission and worked for the Commission (renamed the QWRC: the Queensland Water Resources Commission) for 18 years.  He began his career as a construction engineer on [[Fairbairn Dam]] in [[Central Queensland]], returning to the Brisbane Office of the QWRC in 1970, rising to the rank of Executive Engineer, Water Supply Investigations.  In this role, he oversaw hydrological investigations for the [[Wivenhoe Dam]] is on the [[Brisbane River]] in [[Australia]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/stop-playing-the-flood-blame-game/news-story/8724e48d6ab134afac077c80856e21a9|title=Stop playing the flood blame-game|access-date=2017-03-19}}</ref>  During that time, he was also actively involved in the [[Engineers Australia|Institution of Engineers, Australia]], eventually serving as Chair of its National Committee on Hydrology and Water Resources, during which time he oversaw production of the third edition of ''Australian Rainfall and Runoff''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://arr.ga.gov.au/|title=Australian Rainfall and Runoff - Australian Rainfall and Runoff|website=arr.ga.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2017-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226130338/http://arr.ga.gov.au/|archive-date=26 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Australian Rainfall and Runoff|last=Pilgrim|first=David H.|publisher=The Institution of Engineers, Australia|year=1987|isbn=085825-434-4|location=Barton, ACT. Australia|pages=vii}}</ref>  In 1975, he undertook a [[Winston Churchill Memorial Trusts|Churchill Fellowship]] world tour to study water resources development in the USA, Europe, Israel, and India.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.churchilltrust.com.au/fellows/?keywords=&year=1975|title=Fellows {{!}} Winston Churchill Memorial Trust|website=www.churchilltrust.com.au|access-date=2017-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324084116/https://www.churchilltrust.com.au/fellows/?keywords=&year=1975|archive-date=24 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCommencing his academic career in 1986 with the School of Psychology, Ashkanasy was later seconded to the UQ Technology and Innovation Management Centre (1989). In 1988, he was appointed a Lecturer (Assistant Professor) in the UQ School of Commerce, where he attained tenure and promotion in 1994 before moving to the (former) School of Management in 1995. In 2002, the schools of Commerce and Management merged to form the [[UQ Business School]]. From 2004\u20132008, he served as Associate Dean (Research) of the Faculty of Business, Economics, and Law.  His present position is Professor of Management in the [[UQ Business School]].<ref>Professor Neal Ashkanasy \u2013 UQ Researchers http://researchers.uq.edu.au. Retrieved 25 February, 2020</ref>\n\nAshkanasy is the founder of the \"Emonet\" (the Emotions network)<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.emotionsnet.org/|title=EMONET - Emotions Network|website=www.emotionsnet.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110411232330/http://www.emotionsnet.org/|archive-date=11 April 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> and \"Orgcult\" (Organizational Culture) [[Electronic mailing list|Listservs]], which are sponsored by the [[Academy of Management]].  The Emonet group sponsors the biannual \"International Conference on Emotions and Worklife\" which has been running since 1998.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.emotionsnet.org/sitemap/conferences/|title=Conferences {{!}} EMONET - Emotions Network|website=www.emotionsnet.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319195820/http://www.emotionsnet.org/sitemap/conferences/|archive-date=19 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The 10th \"Emonet Conference\" was held in [[Rome]] in July 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.emotionsnet.org/sitemap/conferences/emonet-x/|title=Emonet X {{!}} EMONET - Emotions Network|website=www.emotionsnet.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319195911/http://www.emotionsnet.org/sitemap/conferences/emonet-x/|archive-date=19 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\nAshkanasy has published over 300 journal articles and book chapters and is author or co-author of over 300 conference papers.  His research interests include emotions in the workplace, leadership and leader-member relations, organizational and national culture, and ethics in organizational behavior.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://researchers.uq.edu.au/researcher/319|title=Professor Neal Ashkanasy - UQ Researchers|website=researchers.uq.edu.au|access-date=2017-03-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313214510/http://researchers.uq.edu.au/researcher/319|archive-date=13 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Google Scholar]], his work has been cited more than 25,000 times.<ref>Neal M. Ashkanasy \u2013 Google Scholar Citations http://scholar.google.com. Retrieved on 04 March 2020.</ref>\n\nAshkanasy served from 2007 to 2014 as [[editor-in-chief]] of the ''[[Journal of Organizational Behavior]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Journal of Organizational Behavior |journal = Journal of Organizational Behavior|doi=10.1002/(ISSN)1099-1379 |citeseerx = 10.1.1.203.3751}}</ref> From 2004 to 2008, he was associate editor of the ''[[Academy of Management Learning and Education]]''. From 2011 to 2014, he served as associate editor of the ''[[Academy of Management Review]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://aom.org/Publications/AMR/Past-Editors-and-Associate-Editors.aspx |title=Past Editors and Associate Editors |website=aom.org |access-date=2017-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170321081847/http://aom.org/Publications/AMR/Past-Editors-and-Associate-Editors.aspx |archive-date=21 March 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> He is currently a member of the [[editorial board]] of ''[[Emotion Review]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://us.sagepub.com/en-us/nam/journal/emotion-review#editorial-board |title=Editorial Board |work=Emotion Review |publisher=[[SAGE Publications]] |accessdate=22 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324000504/https://us.sagepub.com/en-us/nam/journal/emotion-review#editorial-board |archive-date=24 March 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> (action editor) and [[book series]] editor of ''Research on Emotion in Organizations'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emeraldinsight.com/products/books/series.htm?id=1746-9791 |title=Research on Emotion in Organizations |publisher=[[Emerald Group Publishing]] |date=14 October 2011 |accessdate=22 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921064321/http://emeraldinsight.com/products/books/series.htm?id=1746-9791 |archive-date=21 September 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> published by [[Emerald Group Publishing]].\n\n==Awards and honours ==\nAshkanasy received a Medal of the [[Order of Australia]] (OAM) in 2017 \"for service to tertiary education, to psychology, and to the community\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.uq.edu.au/news/article/2017/01/uq-community-members-receive-australia-day-honours|title=UQ community members receive Australia Day honours|date=27 January 2017|publisher=University of Queensland|accessdate=11 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129201507/http://www.uq.edu.au/news/article/2017/01/uq-community-members-receive-australia-day-honours|archive-date=29 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n* Fellow of the [[Academy of Social Sciences]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.acss.org.uk/fellows/|title=Fellows - Academy of Social Sciences|work=Academy of Social Sciences|access-date=2017-03-23|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630101533/https://www.acss.org.uk/fellows/|archive-date=30 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Fellow of the [[Academy of the Social Sciences in Australia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.assa.edu.au/fellows/586/|title=Fellows Detail \u00bb ASSA|website=www.assa.edu.au|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324084749/http://www.assa.edu.au/fellows/586/|archive-date=24 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Fellow of the [[Society for Industrial and Organizational Psychology]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.siop.org/tip/backissues/July06/32fellows.aspx|title=Announcement of New SIOP Fellows July 2006|date=|publisher=Siop.org|accessdate=22 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314080843/http://www.siop.org/tip/backissues/July06/32fellows.aspx|archive-date=14 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Fellow of the [[Association for Psychological Science]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.psychologicalscience.org/fellows/fellows-new.cfm|title=Association for Psychological Science: APS Fellows|website=www.psychologicalscience.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170625182651/http://www.psychologicalscience.org/fellows/fellows-new.cfm|archive-date=25 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Life Fellow of the [[Australia and New Zealand Academy of Management]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.anzam.org/membership/membership-awards/|title=Life Fellow - Australian and New Zealand Academy of Management|work=Australian and New Zealand Academy of Management|access-date=2017-03-24|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324181126/https://www.anzam.org/membership/membership-awards/|archive-date=24 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[British Academy of Management|Fellow of the British Academy of Management]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bam.ac.uk/current-bam-fellows|title=Current BAM Fellows {{!}} bam.ac.uk|website=www.bam.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324175652/https://www.bam.ac.uk/current-bam-fellows|archive-date=24 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Fellow of the [[Southern Management Association]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.southernmanagement.org/default.asp?page=Fellows|title=SMA Fellows - Southern Management Association|website=www.southernmanagement.org|access-date=2017-03-24}}</ref>\n* Awarded the [[Elton Mayo]] award for excellence in teaching and research by the [[Australian Psychological Society]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://psychology.org.au/about/awards/elton_mayo/|title=Australian Psychological Society : Elton Mayo Awards|website=psychology.org.au|access-date=2017-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324175521/http://psychology.org.au/about/awards/elton_mayo/|archive-date=24 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Fellow of the Queensland Academy of Arts and Sciences (Council Member).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://qldacademy.org.au/academy-council/|title=Academy Council|work=Queensland Academy of Arts and Sciences|access-date=2017-03-24|language=en-AU|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324180032/http://qldacademy.org.au/academy-council/|archive-date=24 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Winston Churchill Memorial Trusts|Churchill Fellow]] in the field of water resource development.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.business.uq.edu.au/staff/neal-ashkanasy Official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ashkanasy, Neal}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Organizational psychologists]]\n[[Category:Australian business theorists]]\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Australian Jews]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Medal of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:Civil engineers]]\n[[Category:University of Queensland faculty]]\n[[Category:Fellows of t