{"title_page": "Frank Gebert", "text_new": "{{Infobox tennis biography\n| name = Frank Gebert\n| image =\n| fullname = Frank Gebert\n| country_represented = {{FRG}}\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1952|11|6|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date =\n| death_place = \n| plays =\n| careerprizemoney = \n| singlesrecord = 34\u201361\n| singlestitles = 0\n| highestsinglesranking = No. 85 (31 December 1977)\n| currentsinglesranking = \n| AustralianOpenresult = 2R ([[1973 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1973]])\n| FrenchOpenresult = 3R ([[1976 French Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1976]])\n| Wimbledonresult = 1R ([[1973 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1973]], [[1977 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1977]])\n| USOpenresult = 1R ([[1977 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1977]])\n| doublesrecord = 20\u201348\n| doublestitles = 0\n| highestdoublesranking = \n| currentdoublesranking = \n| AustralianOpenDoublesresult = 2R ([[1973 Australian Open|1973]])\n| FrenchOpenDoublesresult = 2R ([[1976 French Open|1976]])\n| WimbledonDoublesresult = 1R ([[1973 Wimbledon Championships|1973]])\n| USOpenDoublesresult =\n}}\n'''Frank Gebert''' (born 6 November 1952) is a former professional [[tennis]] player from Germany.\n\n==Biography==\nGebert lost to [[Byron Bertram]] in the boys' singles final at the [[1970 Wimbledon Championships]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itftennis.com/media/108160/108160.pdf|title=The Junior Championships, Wimbledon|publisher=[[International Tennis Federation]]|accessdate=6 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1970s, he competed professionally and he appeared in all four [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] tournaments. He made the third round of the [[1976 French Open]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itftennis.com/procircuit/tournaments/men's-tournament/info.aspx?tournamentid=1010004442|title=ITF Tennis - Pro Circuit - French Open - 31 May - 13 June 1976|publisher=[[International Tennis Federation]]|accessdate=6 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nHis best year on tour was 1977, when he was a finalist at the [[Cairo Open]]. He lost the final to [[Fran\u00e7ois Jauffret]], who he then beat along with [[Pat Dupre]] en route to the semi-finals of his next [[Grand Prix tennis circuit|Grand Prix]] tournament in [[Murcia]]. Later in the year, he made further semi-finals in [[Swiss Open (tennis)|Gstaad]] and [[Z\u00fcrich]]. He also managed to win the first set against [[Guillermo Vilas]] when they met in the [[Louisville Open]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1917&dat=19770728&id=rv0wAAAAIBAJ&sjid=QeEFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4847,6814531&hl=en|title=Vilas Wins Louisville Tennis Test|date=28 July 1977|work=[[Schenectady Gazette]]|page=35|accessdate=6 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nA graduate of the [[Free University of Berlin]], Gebert is now a Professor of Economics at SRH University Heidelberg.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hochschule-heidelberg.de/de/fakultaet-fuer-wirtschaft/team/detailansicht/team/frank-gebert/|title=Prof. Dr. Frank Gebert - SRH Hochschule Heidelberg|publisher=SRH University Heidelberg|language=German|accessdate=6 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160206135858/http://www.hochschule-heidelberg.de/de/fakultaet-fuer-wirtschaft/team/detailansicht/team/frank-gebert/|archive-date=6 February 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Grand Prix career finals==\n===Singles: 1 (0\u20131)===\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n!style=\"width:40px\"|Result\n!style=\"width:30px\" class=\"unsortable\"|W/L \n!style=\"width:65px\"|Date\n!style=\"width:140px\"|Tournament\n!style=\"width:55px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:140px\"|Opponent\n!style=\"width:110px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss\n|0\u20131\n|Mar 1977\n|[[Cairo Open|Cairo]], [[Egypt]]\n|Clay\n|{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Fran\u00e7ois Jauffret]]\n|3\u20136, 5\u20137, 4\u20136\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{ATP}}\n* {{ITF}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gebert, Frank}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:West German male tennis players]]\n[[Category:German academics]]\n[[Category:Free University of Berlin alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox tennis biography\n| name = Frank Gebert\n| image =\n| fullname = Frank Gebert\n| country_represented = {{FRG}}\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1952|11|6|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date =\n| death_place = \n| plays =\n| careerprizemoney = \n| singlesrecord = 34\u201361\n| singlestitles = 0\n| highestsinglesranking = No. 85 (31 December 1977)\n| currentsinglesranking = \n| AustralianOpenresult = 2R ([[1973 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1973]])\n| FrenchOpenresult = 3R ([[1976 French Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1976]])\n| Wimbledonresult = 1R ([[1973 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1973]], [[1977 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1977]])\n| USOpenresult = 1R ([[1977 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1977]])\n| doublesrecord = 20\u201348\n| doublestitles = 0\n| highestdoublesranking = \n| currentdoublesranking = \n| AustralianOpenDoublesresult = 2R ([[1973 Australian Open|1973]])\n| FrenchOpenDoublesresult = 2R ([[1976 French Open|1976]])\n| WimbledonDoublesresult = 1R ([[1973 Wimbledon Championships|1973]])\n| USOpenDoublesresult =\n}}\n'''Frank Gebert''' (born 6 November 1952) is a former professional [[tennis]] player from Germany.\n\n==Biography==\nGebert lost to [[Byron Bertram]] in the boys' singles final at the [[1970 Wimbledon Championships]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itftennis.com/media/108160/108160.pdf|title=The Junior Championships, Wimbledon|publisher=[[International Tennis Federation]]|accessdate=6 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1970s, he competed professionally and he appeared in all four [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] tournaments. He made the third round of the [[1976 French Open]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itftennis.com/procircuit/tournaments/men's-tournament/info.aspx?tournamentid=1010004442|title=ITF Tennis - Pro Circuit - French Open - 31 May - 13 June 1976|publisher=[[International Tennis Federation]]|accessdate=6 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nHis best year on tour was 1977, when he was a finalist at the [[Cairo Open]]. He lost the final to [[Fran\u00e7ois Jauffret]], who he then beat along with [[Pat Dupre]] en route to the semi-finals of his next [[Grand Prix tennis circuit|Grand Prix]] tournament in [[Murcia]]. Later in the year, he made further semi-finals in [[Swiss Open (tennis)|Gstaad]] and [[Z\u00fcrich]]. He also managed to win the first set against [[Guillermo Vilas]] when they met in the [[Louisville Open]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1917&dat=19770728&id=rv0wAAAAIBAJ&sjid=QeEFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4847,6814531&hl=en|title=Vilas Wins Louisville Tennis Test|date=28 July 1977|work=[[Schenectady Gazette]]|page=35|accessdate=6 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nA graduate of the [[Free University of Berlin]], Gebert is now a Professor of Economics at SRH University Heidelberg.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hochschule-heidelberg.de/de/fakultaet-fuer-wirtschaft/team/detailansicht/team/frank-gebert/|title=Prof. Dr. Frank Gebert - SRH Hochschule Heidelberg|publisher=SRH University Heidelberg|language=German|accessdate=6 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160206135858/http://www.hochschule-heidelberg.de/de/fakultaet-fuer-wirtschaft/team/detailansicht/team/frank-gebert/|archive-date=6 February 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Grand Prix career finals==\n===Singles: 1 (0\u20131)===\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n!style=\"width:40px\"|Result\n!style=\"width:30px\" class=\"unsortable\"|W/L \n!style=\"width:65px\"|Date\n!style=\"width:160px\"|Tournament\n!style=\"width:55px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:160px\"|Opponent\n!style=\"width:120px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss\n|0\u20131\n|Mar 1977\n|[[Cairo Open|Cairo]], [[Egypt]]\n|Clay\n|{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Fran\u00e7ois Jauffret]]\n|3\u20136, 5\u20137, 4\u20136\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{ATP}}\n* {{ITF}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gebert, Frank}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:West German male tennis players]]\n[[Category:German academics]]\n[[Category:Free University of Berlin alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Wolbo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGrand Prix career finals:Formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_Gebert"}
{"title_page": "Silicon nanowire", "text_new": "'''Silicon nanowires''', also referred to as '''SiNWs''', are a type of semiconductor [[nanowire]] most often formed from a [[silicon]] precursor by etching of a solid or through catalyzed growth from a vapor or liquid phase. Such nanowires have promising applications in lithium ion batteries, [[thermoelectrics]] and [[sensors]]. Initial synthesis of SiNWs is often accompanied by [[thermal oxidation]] steps to yield structures of accurately tailored size and morphology.<ref name=\"slo\">{{cite journal| last1= Liu| first1=M.| last2= Peng |first2=J.| display-authors= etal |title=  ''Two-dimensional modeling of the self-limiting oxidation in silicon and tungsten nanowires'' | journal= Theoretical and Applied Mechanics Letters  | year= 2016 |  volume=6 | issue=5 | pages=195\u2013199 | url= https://www.researchgate.net/publication/306273009 | doi= 10.1016/j.taml.2016.08.002 }}</ref>\n\nSiNWs have unique properties that are not seen in bulk (three-dimensional) silicon materials. These properties arise from an unusual quasi one-dimensional electronic structure and are the subject of research across numerous disciplines and applications. The reason that SiNWs are considered as one of the most important one-dimensional materials is they could have a function as building blocks for nanoscale electronics assembled without the need for complex and costly fabrication facilities.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yi|first=Cui|last2=Charles M.|first2=Lieber|year=2001|title=Functional Nanoscale Electronic Devices Assembled Using Silicon Nanowire Building Blocks|url=|journal=Science|volume=291|issue=5505|pages=851\u2013853|doi=10.1126/science.291.5505.851|pmid=11157160|bibcode=2001Sci...291..851C}}</ref> SiNWs are frequently studied towards applications including [[photovoltaics]], [[nanowire batteries]], thermoelectrics and non-volatile memory.<ref name=\"miko\">{{cite journal| last1=Mikolajick | first1=Thomas | last2= Heinzig |first2= Andre |last3= Trommer | first3= Jens | display-authors= etal  |title= Silicon nanowires\u2013a versatile technology platform | journal= Physica Status Solidi RRL  | year= 2013| volume=7 |issue=10 | pages= 793\u2013799 | doi=10.1002/pssr.201307247|bibcode=2013PSSRR...7..793M}}</ref>\n\n==Applications==\n\nOwing to their unique physical and chemical properties, silicon nanowires are a promising candidate for a wide range of applications that draw on their unique physico-chemical characteristics, which differ from those of bulk silicon material.<ref name=\"slo\" />\n\nSiNWs exhibit charge trapping behavior which renders such systems of value in applications necessitating electron hole separation such as photovoltaics, and photocatalysts.<ref>{{cite journal| last1= Tsakalakos | first1= L. | last2= Balch |first2= J. |last3= Fronheiser | first3= J. | last4= Korevaar | first4=B.|title= Silicon nanowire solar cells | journal= Applied Physics Letters | year= 2007| volume= 91 |issue= 23 | pages= 233117 | doi=10.1063/1.2821113|bibcode= 2007ApPhL..91w3117T }}</ref> Recent experiment on nanowire solar cells has led to a remarkable improvement of the power conversion efficiency of SiNW solar cells from <1% to >17% in the last few years.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yu|first=Peng|last2=Wu|first2=Jiang|last3=Liu|first3=Shenting|last4=Xiong|first4=Jie|last5=Jagadish|first5=Chennupati|last6=Wang|first6=Zhiming M.|date=2016-12-01|title=Design and fabrication of silicon nanowires towards efficient solar cells|journal=Nano Today|volume=11|issue=6|pages=704\u2013737|doi=10.1016/j.nantod.2016.10.001|url=http://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/1536157/1/NANOTODAY_2016_Accepted%20version.pdf}}</ref>\n\nCharge trapping behaviour and tuneable surface governed transport properties of SiNWs render this category of nanostructures of interest towards use as metal insulator semiconductors and [[MOSFET|field effect transistors]],<ref>\n{{cite journal |doi=10.1021/nl025875l|title=High Performance Silicon Nanowire Field Effect Transistors|journal=Nano Letters|volume=3|issue=2|pages=149\u2013152|year=2003|last1=Cui|first1=Yi|last2=Zhong|first2=Zhaohui|last3=Wang|first3=Deli|last4=Wang|first4=Wayne U.|last5=Lieber|first5=Charles M.|bibcode=2003NanoL...3..149C}}\n</ref> with further applications as nanoelectronic storage devices,<ref>{{cite journal| last1=Tian | first1=Bozhi | last2= Xiaolin |first2= Zheng|display-authors= etal  |title= Coaxial silicon nanowires as solar cells and nanoelectronic power sources | journal= Nature| year= 2007 | volume= 449 |issue= 7164| pages= 885\u2013889 | doi=10.1038/nature06181| pmid=17943126 |bibcode= 2007Natur.449..885T}}</ref> in [[flash memory]], [[Programmable logic device|logic devices]] as well as chemical and biological sensors.<ref name=\"miko\" /><ref>{{cite journal| last1=Daniel | first1=Shir | display-authors=etal  |title= Oxidation of silicon nanowires | journal= Journal of Vacuum Science & Technology | year= 2006 | volume= 24 |issue= 3 | pages= 1333\u20131336 | doi= 10.1116/1.2198847 | bibcode=2006JVSTB..24.1333S }}</ref>\n\nThe ability for [[lithium]] ions to [[Intercalation (chemistry)|intercalate]] into silicon structures renders various Si [[nanostructures]] of interest towards applications as [[anodes]] in [[Lithium-ion battery|Li-ion batteries (LiBs)]]. SiNWs are of particular merit as such anodes as they exhibit the ability to undergo significant lithiation while maintaining structural integrity and electrical connectivity.<ref>{{cite journal| last1=Chan | first1= C.| last2= Peng |first2= H. |display-authors= etal |title= High-performance lithium battery anodes using silicon nanowires | journal= Nature Nanotechnology | year= 2008| volume= 3|issue= 1| pages= 31\u201335 | doi=10.1038/nnano.2007.411| pmid= 18654447|bibcode= 2008NatNa...3...31C}}</ref>\n\nSilicon nanowires are efficient [[thermoelectric generator]]s because they combine a high electrical conductivity, owing to the bulk properties of doped Si, with low thermal conductivity due to the small cross section.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1080/14686996.2018.1460177|pmid=29868148|title=Miniaturized planar Si-nanowire micro-thermoelectric generator using exuded thermal field for power generation|journal=Science and Technology of Advanced Materials|volume=19|issue=1|pages=443\u2013453|year=2018|last1=Zhan|first1=Tianzhuo|last2=Yamato|first2=Ryo|last3=Hashimoto|first3=Shuichiro|last4=Tomita|first4=Motohiro|last5=Oba|first5=Shunsuke|last6=Himeda|first6=Yuya|last7=Mesaki|first7=Kohei|last8=Takezawa|first8=Hiroki|last9=Yokogawa|first9=Ryo|last10=Xu|first10=Yibin|last11=Matsukawa|first11=Takashi|last12=Ogura|first12=Atsushi|last13=Kamakura|first13=Yoshinari|last14=Watanabe|first14=Takanobu|pmc=5974757|bibcode=2018STAdM..19..443Z}}</ref>\n\n==Synthesis==\n\nSeveral synthesis methods are known for SiNWs and these can be broadly divided into methods which start with bulk silicon and remove material to yield nanowires, also known as top-down synthesis, and methods which use a chemical or vapor precursor to build nanowires in a process generally considered to be bottom-up synthesis.<ref name=\"miko\" />\n\n===Top down synthesis methods===\n\nThese methods use material removal techniques to produce nanostructures from a bulk precursor\n\n*[[Laser ablation|Laser beam ablation]]<ref name=\"miko\" />\n*Ion beam etching<ref>{{cite journal| last1= Huang  | first1=Z. | last2= Fang |first2=H. |last3= Zhu | first3= J.  |title= Fabrication of silicon nanowire arrays with controlled diameter, length, and density | journal= Advanced Materials  | year=2007| volume=19 |issue=5 | pages= 744\u2013748 | doi=10.1002/adma.200600892}}</ref>\n*Thermal evaporation oxide-assisted growth (OAG)<ref name=\"shao\">{{cite journal| last1= Shao | first1=M.| last2=Duo Duo Ma |first2= D. |last3= Lee | first3= ST |title= Silicon nanowires\u2013synthesis, properties, and applications | journal= European Journal of Inorganic Chemistry | year= 2010 | volume= 2010| issue=27| pages= 4264\u20134278  | doi=10.1002/ejic.201000634}}</ref>\n*Metal-assisted chemical etching (MaCE)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Huang|first=Zhipeng|last2=Geyer|first2=Nadine|last3=Werner|first3=Peter|last4=Boor|first4=Johannes de|last5=G\u00f6sele|first5=Ulrich|date=2011|title=Metal-Assisted Chemical Etching of Silicon: A Review|journal=Advanced Materials|language=en|volume=23|issue=2|pages=285\u2013308|doi=10.1002/adma.201001784|pmid=20859941|issn=1521-4095}}</ref>\n\n===Bottom-up synthesis methods===\n\n*[[Vapor\u2013liquid\u2013solid method|Vapour liquid solid (VLS)]] growth \u2013 a type of catalysed [[Chemical vapor deposition|CVD]] often using [[silane]] as Si precursor and gold nanoparticles as catalyst (or 'seed').<ref name=\"miko\" /> \n*[[Molecular beam epitaxy]] \u2013 a form of [[Physical vapor deposition|PVD]] applied in plasma environment<ref name=\"shao\" />\n*Precipitation from a solution \u2013 A variation of the VLS method, aptly named supercritical fluid liquid solid (SFLS), that uses a [[supercritical fluid]] (e.g. organosilane at high temperature and pressure) as Si precursor instead of vapor. The catalyst would be a colloid in solution, such as [[colloidal gold]] nanoparticles, and the SiNWs are grown in this solution<ref name=\"shao\" /><ref>{{cite journal| last1=Holmes | first1=J. | last2=Keith  |first2= P. |last3=Johnston | first3=R. | last4=Doty| first4=C.|title= Control of thickness and orientation of solution-grown silicon nanowires | journal= Science | year=2000| volume=287 |issue= 5457| pages= 1471\u20131473 | doi=10.1126/science.287.5457.1471| pmid=10688792 |bibcode=2000Sci...287.1471H}}</ref>\n\n===Thermal oxidation===\n\nSubsequent to physical or chemical processing, either top-down or bottom-up, to obtain initial silicon nanostructures, thermal oxidation steps are often applied in order to obtain materials with desired size and [[aspect ratio]]. Silicon nanowires exhibit a distinct and useful self-limiting [[oxidation]] behaviour whereby oxidation effectively ceases due to [[diffusion]] limitations, which can be modeled.<ref name=\"slo\" /> This phenomenon allows accurate control of dimensions and aspect ratios in SiNWs and has been used to obtain high aspect ratio SiNWs with diameters below 5&nbsp;nm.<ref>{{cite journal| last1=Liu | first1= H.I. | last2= Biegelsen |first2=D.K. |last3=Ponce | first3=F.A. | last4=Johnson | first4=N.M.|  last5=Pease | first5=R.F.W.|title= Self-limiting oxidation for fabricating sub-5 nm silicon nanowires | journal= Applied Physics Letters| volume= 64 | year=1994|issue=11| pages=  1383| bibcode= 1994ApPhL..64.1383L | doi= 10.1063/1.111914 }}</ref> The self-limiting oxidation of SiNWs is of value towards lithium ion battery materials.\n\n==Orientation of nanowires==\n\nThe orientation of SiNWs has profound influence on the structural and electronic properties of  the systems.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Justo|first1=J.F.|last2=Menezes|first2=R.D.|last3=Assali|first3=L.V.C.|title=Stability and plasticity of silicon nanowires: The role of wire perimeter|journal=Phys. Rev. B|date=2007|volume=75|issue=4|page=045303|doi=10.1103/PhysRevB.75.045303|arxiv=1307.3274|bibcode=2007PhRvB..75d5303J}}</ref> For this reason several procedures have been proposed for the alignment of nanowires in chosen orientations. This includes the use of electric fields in polar alignment, [[electrophoresis]], mircofluidic methods and contact printing.\n\n==Outlook==\n\nThere is significant interest in SiNWs for their unique properties and the ability to control size and aspect ratio with great accuracy. As yet, limitations in large-scale fabrication impede the uptake of this material in the full range of investigated applications. Combined studies of synthesis methods, oxidation kinetics and properties of SiNW systems aim to overcome the present limitations and facilitate the implementation of SiNW systems, for example, high quality vapor-liquid-solid\u2013grown SiNWs with smooth surfaces can be reversibly stretched with 10% or more elastic strain, approaching the theoretical elastic limit of silicon, which could open the doors for the emerging \u201celastic strain engineering\u201d and flexible bio-/nano-electronics.<ref>{{cite journal| last1=Zhang | first1= H. | last2= Tersoff |first2=J. |last3=Xu | first3=S. | display-authors=etal |title= Approaching the ideal elastic strain limit in silicon nanowires | journal=Science Advances | year=2016| volume=2 |issue=8| pages=e1501382 | doi=10.1126/sciadv.1501382| pmid= 27540586 | pmc= 4988777 |bibcode=2016SciA....2E1382Z }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Materials]]\n[[Category:Nanotechnology]]\n[[Category:Nanoelectronics]]\n[[Category:Nanomaterials]]\n[[Category:Nanowire]]\n[[Category:Silicon]]\n", "text_old": "'''Silicon nanowires''', also referred to as '''SiNWs''', are a type of semiconductor [[nanowire]] most often formed from a [[silicon]] precursor by etching of a solid or through catalyzed growth from a vapor or liquid phase. Such nanowires have promising applications in lithium ion batteries, [[thermoelectrics]] and [[sensors]]. Initial synthesis of SiNWs is often accompanied by [[thermal oxidation]] steps to yield structures of accurately tailored size and morphology.<ref name=\"slo\">{{cite journal| last1= Liu| first1=M.| last2= Peng |first2=J.| display-authors= etal |title=  ''Two-dimensional modeling of the self-limiting oxidation in silicon and tungsten nanowires'' | journal= Theoretical and Applied Mechanics Letters  | year= 2016 |  volume=6 | issue=5 | pages=195\u2013199 | url= https://www.researchgate.net/publication/306273009 | doi= 10.1016/j.taml.2016.08.002 }}</ref>\n\nSiNWs have unique properties that are not seen in bulk (three-dimensional) silicon materials. These properties arise from an unusual quasi one-dimensional electronic structure and are the subject of research across numerous disciplines and applications. The reason that SiNWs are considered as one of the most important one-dimensional materials is they could have a function as building blocks for nanoscale electronics assembled without the need for complex and costly fabrication facilities.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yi|first=Cui|last2=Charles M.|first2=Lieber|year=2001|title=Functional Nanoscale Electronic Devices Assembled Using Silicon Nanowire Building Blocks|url=|journal=Science|volume=291|issue=5505|pages=851\u2013853|doi=10.1126/science.291.5505.851|pmid=11157160|bibcode=2001Sci...291..851C}}</ref> SiNWs are frequently studied towards applications including [[photovoltaics]], [[nanowire batteries]], [[thermoelectrics]] and non-volatile memory.<ref name=\"miko\">{{cite journal| last1=Mikolajick | first1=Thomas | last2= Heinzig |first2= Andre |last3= Trommer | first3= Jens | display-authors= etal  |title= Silicon nanowires\u2013a versatile technology platform | journal= Physica Status Solidi RRL  | year= 2013| volume=7 |issue=10 | pages= 793\u2013799 | doi=10.1002/pssr.201307247|bibcode=2013PSSRR...7..793M}}</ref>\n\n==Applications==\n\nOwing to their unique physical and chemical properties, silicon nanowires are a promising candidate for a wide range of applications that draw on their unique physico-chemical characteristics, which differ from those of bulk [[silicon]] material.<ref name=\"slo\" />\n\nSiNWs exhibit charge trapping behavior which renders such systems of value in applications necessitating electron hole separation such as photovoltaics, and photocatalysts.<ref>{{cite journal| last1= Tsakalakos | first1= L. | last2= Balch |first2= J. |last3= Fronheiser | first3= J. | last4= Korevaar | first4=B.|title= Silicon nanowire solar cells | journal= Applied Physics Letters | year= 2007| volume= 91 |issue= 23 | pages= 233117 | doi=10.1063/1.2821113|bibcode= 2007ApPhL..91w3117T }}</ref> Recent experiment on nanowire solar cells has led to a remarkable improvement of the power conversion efficiency of SiNW solar cells from <1% to >17% in the last few years.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yu|first=Peng|last2=Wu|first2=Jiang|last3=Liu|first3=Shenting|last4=Xiong|first4=Jie|last5=Jagadish|first5=Chennupati|last6=Wang|first6=Zhiming M.|date=2016-12-01|title=Design and fabrication of silicon nanowires towards efficient solar cells|journal=Nano Today|volume=11|issue=6|pages=704\u2013737|doi=10.1016/j.nantod.2016.10.001|url=http://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/1536157/1/NANOTODAY_2016_Accepted%20version.pdf}}</ref>\n\nCharge trapping behaviour and tuneable surface governed transport properties of SiNWs render this category of nanostructures of interest towards use as metal insulator semiconductors and [[MOSFET|field effect transistors]],<ref>\n{{cite journal |doi=10.1021/nl025875l|title=High Performance Silicon Nanowire Field Effect Transistors|journal=Nano Letters|volume=3|issue=2|pages=149\u2013152|year=2003|last1=Cui|first1=Yi|last2=Zhong|first2=Zhaohui|last3=Wang|first3=Deli|last4=Wang|first4=Wayne U.|last5=Lieber|first5=Charles M.|bibcode=2003NanoL...3..149C}}\n</ref> with further applications as nanoelectronic storage devices,<ref>{{cite journal| last1=Tian | first1=Bozhi | last2= Xiaolin |first2= Zheng|display-authors= etal  |title= Coaxial silicon nanowires as solar cells and nanoelectronic power sources | journal= Nature| year= 2007 | volume= 449 |issue= 7164| pages= 885\u2013889 | doi=10.1038/nature06181| pmid=17943126 |bibcode= 2007Natur.449..885T}}</ref> in [[flash memory]], [[Programmable logic device|logic devices]] as well as chemical and biological [[sensors]].<ref name=\"miko\" /><ref>{{cite journal| last1=Daniel | first1=Shir | display-authors=etal  |title= Oxidation of silicon nanowires | journal= Journal of Vacuum Science & Technology | year= 2006 | volume= 24 |issue= 3 | pages= 1333\u20131336 | doi= 10.1116/1.2198847 | bibcode=2006JVSTB..24.1333S }}</ref>\n\nThe ability for [[lithium]] ions to [[Intercalation (chemistry)|intercalate]] into silicon structures renders various Si [[nanostructures]] of interest towards applications as [[anodes]] in [[Lithium-ion battery|Li-ion batteries (LiBs)]]. SiNWs are of particular merit as such anodes as they exhibit the ability to undergo significant lithiation while maintaining structural integrity and electrical connectivity.<ref>{{cite journal| last1=Chan | first1= C.| last2= Peng |first2= H. |display-authors= etal |title= High-performance lithium battery anodes using silicon nanowires | journal= Nature Nanotechnology | year= 2008| volume= 3|issue= 1| pages= 31\u201335 | doi=10.1038/nnano.2007.411| pmid= 18654447|bibcode= 2008NatNa...3...31C}}</ref>\n\nSilicon nanowires are efficient [[thermoelectric generator]]s because they combine a high electrical conductivity, owing to the bulk properties of doped Si, with low thermal conductivity due to the small cross section.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1080/14686996.2018.1460177|pmid=29868148|title=Miniaturized planar Si-nanowire micro-thermoelectric generator using exuded thermal field for power generation|journal=Science and Technology of Advanced Materials|volume=19|issue=1|pages=443\u2013453|year=2018|last1=Zhan|first1=Tianzhuo|last2=Yamato|first2=Ryo|last3=Hashimoto|first3=Shuichiro|last4=Tomita|first4=Motohiro|last5=Oba|first5=Shunsuke|last6=Himeda|first6=Yuya|last7=Mesaki|first7=Kohei|last8=Takezawa|first8=Hiroki|last9=Yokogawa|first9=Ryo|last10=Xu|first10=Yibin|last11=Matsukawa|first11=Takashi|last12=Ogura|first12=Atsushi|last13=Kamakura|first13=Yoshinari|last14=Watanabe|first14=Takanobu|pmc=5974757|bibcode=2018STAdM..19..443Z}}</ref>\n\n==Synthesis==\n\nSeveral synthesis methods are known for SiNWs and these can be broadly divided into methods which start with bulk silicon and remove material to yield nanowires, also known as top-down synthesis, and methods which use a chemical or vapor precursor to build nanowires in a process generally considered to be bottom-up synthesis.<ref name=\"miko\" />\n\n===Top down synthesis methods===\n\nThese methods use material removal techniques to produce nanostructures from a bulk precursor\n\n*[[Laser ablation|Laser beam ablation]]<ref name=\"miko\" />\n*Ion beam etching<ref>{{cite journal| last1= Huang  | first1=Z. | last2= Fang |first2=H. |last3= Zhu | first3= J.  |title= Fabrication of silicon nanowire arrays with controlled diameter, length, and density | journal= Advanced Materials  | year=2007| volume=19 |issue=5 | pages= 744\u2013748 | doi=10.1002/adma.200600892}}</ref>\n*Thermal evaporation oxide-assisted growth (OAG)<ref name=\"shao\">{{cite journal| last1= Shao | first1=M.| last2=Duo Duo Ma |first2= D. |last3= Lee | first3= ST |title= Silicon nanowires\u2013synthesis, properties, and applications | journal= European Journal of Inorganic Chemistry | year= 2010 | volume= 2010| issue=27| pages= 4264\u20134278  | doi=10.1002/ejic.201000634}}</ref>\n*Metal-assisted chemical etching (MaCE)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Huang|first=Zhipeng|last2=Geyer|first2=Nadine|last3=Werner|first3=Peter|last4=Boor|first4=Johannes de|last5=G\u00f6sele|first5=Ulrich|date=2011|title=Metal-Assisted Chemical Etching of Silicon: A Review|journal=Advanced Materials|language=en|volume=23|issue=2|pages=285\u2013308|doi=10.1002/adma.201001784|pmid=20859941|issn=1521-4095}}</ref>\n\n===Bottom-up synthesis methods===\n\n*[[Vapor\u2013liquid\u2013solid method|Vapour liquid solid (VLS)]] growth \u2013 a type of catalysed [[Chemical vapor deposition|CVD]] often using [[silane]] as Si precursor and gold nanoparticles as catalyst (or 'seed').<ref name=\"miko\" /> \n*[[Molecular beam epitaxy]] \u2013 a form of [[Physical vapor deposition|PVD]] applied in plasma environment<ref name=\"shao\" />\n*Precipitation from a solution \u2013 A variation of the VLS method, aptly named supercritical fluid liquid solid (SFLS), that uses a [[supercritical fluid]] (e.g. organosilane at high temperature and pressure) as Si precursor instead of vapor. The catalyst would be a colloid in solution, such as [[colloidal gold]] nanoparticles, and the SiNWs are grown in this solution<ref name=\"shao\" /><ref>{{cite journal| last1=Holmes | first1=J. | last2=Keith  |first2= P. |last3=Johnston | first3=R. | last4=Doty| first4=C.|title= Control of thickness and orientation of solution-grown silicon nanowires | journal= Science | year=2000| volume=287 |issue= 5457| pages= 1471\u20131473 | doi=10.1126/science.287.5457.1471| pmid=10688792 |bibcode=2000Sci...287.1471H}}</ref>\n\n===Thermal oxidation===\n\nSubsequent to physical or chemical processing, either top-down or bottom-up, to obtain initial silicon nanostructures, thermal oxidation steps are often applied in order to obtain materials with desired size and [[aspect ratio]]. Silicon nanowires exhibit a distinct and useful self-limiting [[oxidation]] behaviour whereby oxidation effectively ceases due to [[diffusion]] limitations, which can be modeled.<ref name=\"slo\" /> This phenomenon allows accurate control of dimensions and aspect ratios in SiNWs and has been used to obtain high aspect ratio SiNWs with diameters below 5&nbsp;nm.<ref>{{cite journal| last1=Liu | first1= H.I. | last2= Biegelsen |first2=D.K. |last3=Ponce | first3=F.A. | last4=Johnson | first4=N.M.|  last5=Pease | first5=R.F.W.|title= Self-limiting oxidation for fabricating sub-5 nm silicon nanowires | journal= Applied Physics Letters| volume= 64 | year=1994|issue=11| pages=  1383| bibcode= 1994ApPhL..64.1383L | doi= 10.1063/1.111914 }}</ref> The self-limiting oxidation of SiNWs is of value towards lithium ion battery materials.\n\n==Orientation of nanowires==\n\nThe orientation of SiNWs has profound influence on the structural and electronic properties of  the systems.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Justo|first1=J.F.|last2=Menezes|first2=R.D.|last3=Assali|first3=L.V.C.|title=Stability and plasticity of silicon nanowires: The role of wire perimeter|journal=Phys. Rev. B|date=2007|volume=75|issue=4|page=045303|doi=10.1103/PhysRevB.75.045303|arxiv=1307.3274|bibcode=2007PhRvB..75d5303J}}</ref> For this reason several procedures have been proposed for the alignment of nanowires in chosen orientations. This includes the use of electric fields in polar alignment, [[electrophoresis]], mircofluidic methods and contact printing.\n\n==Outlook==\n\nThere is significant interest in SiNWs for their unique properties and the ability to control size and aspect ratio with great accuracy. As yet, limitations in large-scale fabrication impede the uptake of this material in the full range of investigated applications. Combined studies of synthesis methods, oxidation kinetics and properties of SiNW systems aim to overcome the present limitations and facilitate the implementation of SiNW systems, for example, high quality vapor-liquid-solid\u2013grown SiNWs with smooth surfaces can be reversibly stretched with 10% or more elastic strain, approaching the theoretical elastic limit of silicon, which could open the doors for the emerging \u201celastic strain engineering\u201d and flexible bio-/nano-electronics.<ref>{{cite journal| last1=Zhang | first1= H. | last2= Tersoff |first2=J. |last3=Xu | first3=S. | display-authors=etal |title= Approaching the ideal elastic strain limit in silicon nanowires | journal=Science Advances | year=2016| volume=2 |issue=8| pages=e1501382 | doi=10.1126/sciadv.1501382| pmid= 27540586 | pmc= 4988777 |bibcode=2016SciA....2E1382Z }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Materials]]\n[[Category:Nanotechnology]]\n[[Category:Nanoelectronics]]\n[[Category:Nanomaterials]]\n[[Category:Nanowire]]\n[[Category:Silicon]]\n", "name_user": "WildStar", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup:  Per Wikipedia guidelines, removed duplicate hyperlinks.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silicon_nanowire"}
{"title_page": "Symbiont (company)", "text_new": "{{About|the company|the term in biology|symbiosis}}\n{{Puffery|date=August 2019}}{{Infobox company\n| name = Symbiont.io, Inc.\n| logo = Symbiont (company) logo.png\n| type = [[Delaware General Corporation Law|Delaware Corporation]]\n| industry = Blockchain technology\n| founded = 2015\n| founder = Mark Smith, Adam Krellenstein, Evan Wagner, Robby Dermody\n| hq_location_city = [[New York City]]\n| hq_location_country = [[United States]]\n| brands = Smart Security, Smart Securities,<ref name=\"smart-securities-issuer\">{{cite news|last=Allison|first=Ian|title=Smart securities issuer Symbiont fires shots in the private blockchain arms race|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/smart-securities-issuer-symbiont-fires-shots-private-blockchain-arms-race-1521449|date=2015-09-28|newspaper=International Business Times|accessdate=2016-06-01}}</ref> Assembly, SymPL\n| website = {{url|http://symbiont.io}}\n}}\n\n'''Symbiont''' is a [[Blockchain (database)|blockchain]] technology company based in [[New York City]], New York.<ref name=\"novogratz\" /> Symbiont develops the Assembly blockchain platform, as well as programmable versions of traditional financial instruments that run on Assembly as [[smart contracts]].<ref name=\"us-tech-company\">{{cite news|last=Chavez-Dreyfuss|first=Gertrude|title=U.S. tech company raises $1.25 mln from ex-NYSE Euronext CEO, ex-Citadel trader|url=http://reuters.com/article/symbiont-blockchain-idINL1N0YV1CF20150609|date=2015-06-10|work=Reuters|accessdate=2016-06-01}}</ref><ref name=\"financial-heavyweights\">{{cite web|last=Leising|first=Matthew|title=Some Financial Heavyweights Just Invested in a Trading Platform Linked to Bitcoin|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-06-09/symbiont-s-bitcoin-linked-trading-fix-gets-heavyweight-backing|date=2015-06-09|website=Bloomberg|accessdate=2016-06-01}}</ref> Assembly distributes data across a network of computers owned and controlled by different financial institutions while preserving data confidentiality, and the smart contracts written in its proprietary language, SymPL, automate business workflows.<ref name=profit-and-loss>{{cite web|title=Can Symbiont\u2019s Blockchain Solution Change How FX Trades? | last=Stops | first = Galen | work = Profit & Loss: In the Currency & Derivative Markets | date = 2020-01-15 | accessdate = 2020-02-09 | url = https://www.profit-loss.com/can-symbionts-blockchain-solution-change-how-fx-trades/}}</ref> Symbiont Assembly is used by financial institutions, including [[Nasdaq]], [[Citigroup]] and [[The Vanguard Group|Vanguard]].<ref name=blockchain50 />\n\n== History ==\nSymbiont was founded in 2015 by Mark Smith (CEO), Adam Krellenstein, Evan Wagner and Robby Dermody.<ref name=\"novogratz\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-23/nasdaq-citi-join-novogratz-in-funding-blockchain-firm-symbiont|title=Nasdaq, Citi Join Novogratz in Funding Blockchain Firm Symbiont|last=Marsh|first=Alastair|date=2019-01-23|website=Bloomberg|access-date=2019-06-28}}</ref><ref name=nasdaq>{{cite web|last=Shen|first=Lucinda|url=https://fortune.com/2019/01/23/nasdaq-citi-symbiont-blockchain-venture-capital-cryptocurrency/|title=Blockchain Startup Symbiont Raises $20 Million to Take Aim at a Cause of the Financial Crisis|publisher=Fortune|date=2019-01-23|language=en|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref> Symbiont early investors include [[Duncan Niederauer]], former CEO of the [[New York Stock Exchange]], and former co-head of [[Citadel LLC|Citadel]] Matt Andresen.<ref name=\"us-tech-company\" /><ref name=\"ex-nyse\">{{cite news|last=Bullock|first=Nicole|title=Ex-NYSE head among trading veterans backing blockchain start-up|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/0823a136-0ead-11e5-9ae0-00144feabdc0.html|date=2015-06-09|newspaper=Financial Times|accessdate=2016-06-01}}</ref>  In January 2019,  [[Nasdaq|Nasdaq Ventures]] led a US$20 million [[Series B]] round. [[Citigroup]], [[Mike Novogratz]]\u2019s crypto-focus merchant bank, Galaxy Digital Holdings Ltd. and Raptor Group Holdings also participated in the round.<ref name=\"novogratz\" /> Symbiont has 75 employees as of June 2019.<ref name=\"trillion\" />\n\n==Products and customers==\nSymbiont's blockchain products manage the life cycle of financial instruments including mortgages, private equity, syndicated loans and market data.<ref name=trillion />\n\nIn December 2017, Vanguard announced a pilot program with Symbiont to build a product for managing [[Stock market index|index data]] on its blockchain platform.<ref name=\"eha\">{{cite web|last=Eha|first=Brian Patrick|title=Vanguard leapfrogs cautious banks, unveils blockchain network plan|url=https://www.americanbanker.com/news/vanguard-mutual-fund-giant-plans-blockchain-network|date=2017-12-12|website=American Banker|accessdate=2017-12-14}}</ref> Vanguard now uses Symbiont blockchain technology in production to manage US$1.5 trillion of [[index funds]],<ref name=blockchain50>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/michaeldelcastillo/2020/02/19/blockchain-50/#303c8c787553|title=Blockchain 50|last1=del Castillo|first1=Michael|last2=Schifrin|first2=Matt|website=Forbes|access-date=2020-02-19|date=2020-02-19}}</ref> where Symbiont's technology eliminates manual reconciliation between Vanguard and the [[Center for Research in Security Prices]] (CRSP), who publishes data to the blockchain network.<ref name=nasdaq /> This was the first production integration of blockchain technology by a major financial institution into one of their core systems.<ref name=\"trillion\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeffkauflin/2019/05/30/vanguard-is-now-using-blockchain-technology-to-help-manage-13-trillion-in-index-funds/|title=Vanguard Is Now Using Blockchain Technology To Help Manage $1.3 Trillion In Index Funds|last=Kauflin|first=Jeff|date=2019-05-30|website=Forbes|access-date=2019-06-28}}</ref>\n\nSymbiont's technology also powers a venture by Vanguard aiming at making peer-to-peer trading between [[asset management|asset managers]] in the [[foreign exchange market]] possible for the first time.<ref name=marsh2>{{cite news|newspaper=Bloomberg|last=Marsh|first=Alastair|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-10-03/vanguard-to-challenge-banks-grip-on-6-trillion-currency-market|date=2019-10-03|accessdate=2019-10-24|title=Vanguard to Challenge Banks\u2019 Grip on $6 Trillion Currency Market}}</ref> The Assembly [[Investment banking|FICC]] network allows for the decentralized [[collateral management]] among asset managers trading in foreign exchange while mitigating [[counterparty risk]].<ref name=profit-and-loss />\n<!--\n==Technology==\nEach market participant runs its own node in a given network, and a shared log is replicated across all nodes identically, but each firm can only decrypt transactions that it is a participant in.<ref name=profit-and-loss />\n-->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://symbiont.io/}}\n* [http://synapsloans.io Synaps Loans website]\n\n[[Category:Blockchain entities]]\n[[Category:Companies based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Financial technology companies]]\n[[Category:Financial software companies]]\n[[Category:2015 establishments in New York City]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 2015]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2015]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the company|the term in biology|symbiosis}}\n{{Puffery|date=August 2019}}{{Infobox company\n| name = Symbiont.io, Inc.\n| logo = Symbiont (company) logo.png\n| type = [[Delaware General Corporation Law|Delaware Corporation]]\n| industry = Blockchain technology\n| founded = 2015\n| founder = Mark Smith, Adam Krellenstein, Evan Wagner, Robby Dermody\n| hq_location_city = [[New York City]]\n| hq_location_country = [[United States]]\n| brands = Smart Security, Smart Securities,<ref name=\"smart-securities-issuer\">{{cite news|last=Allison|first=Ian|title=Smart securities issuer Symbiont fires shots in the private blockchain arms race|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/smart-securities-issuer-symbiont-fires-shots-private-blockchain-arms-race-1521449|date=2015-09-28|newspaper=International Business Times|accessdate=2016-06-01}}</ref> Assembly, SymPL\n| website = {{url|http://symbiont.io}}\n}}\n\n'''Symbiont''' is a [[Blockchain (database)|blockchain]] technology company based in [[New York City]], New York.<ref name=\"novogratz\" /> Symbiont develops the Assembly blockchain platform, as well as programmable versions of traditional financial instruments that run on Assembly as [[smart contracts]].<ref name=\"us-tech-company\">{{cite news|last=Chavez-Dreyfuss|first=Gertrude|title=U.S. tech company raises $1.25 mln from ex-NYSE Euronext CEO, ex-Citadel trader|url=http://reuters.com/article/symbiont-blockchain-idINL1N0YV1CF20150609|date=2015-06-10|work=Reuters|accessdate=2016-06-01}}</ref><ref name=\"financial-heavyweights\">{{cite web|last=Leising|first=Matthew|title=Some Financial Heavyweights Just Invested in a Trading Platform Linked to Bitcoin|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-06-09/symbiont-s-bitcoin-linked-trading-fix-gets-heavyweight-backing|date=2015-06-09|website=Bloomberg|accessdate=2016-06-01}}</ref> Assembly distributes data across a network of computers owned and controlled by different financial institutions while preserving the confidentiality of proprietary data, and the smart contracts written in its proprietary language, SymPL, automate business workflows.<ref name=profit-and-loss>{{cite web|title=Can Symbiont\u2019s Blockchain Solution Change How FX Trades? | last=Stops | first = Galen | work = Profit & Loss: In the Currency & Derivative Markets | date = 2020-01-15 | accessdate = 2020-02-09 | url = https://www.profit-loss.com/can-symbionts-blockchain-solution-change-how-fx-trades/}}</ref> Symbiont Assembly is used by financial institutions, including [[Nasdaq]], [[Citigroup]] and [[The Vanguard Group|Vanguard]].<ref name=blockchain50 />\n\n== History ==\nSymbiont was founded in 2015 by Mark Smith (CEO), Adam Krellenstein, Evan Wagner and Robby Dermody.<ref name=\"novogratz\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-23/nasdaq-citi-join-novogratz-in-funding-blockchain-firm-symbiont|title=Nasdaq, Citi Join Novogratz in Funding Blockchain Firm Symbiont|last=Marsh|first=Alastair|date=2019-01-23|website=Bloomberg|access-date=2019-06-28}}</ref><ref name=nasdaq>{{cite web|last=Shen|first=Lucinda|url=https://fortune.com/2019/01/23/nasdaq-citi-symbiont-blockchain-venture-capital-cryptocurrency/|title=Blockchain Startup Symbiont Raises $20 Million to Take Aim at a Cause of the Financial Crisis|publisher=Fortune|date=2019-01-23|language=en|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref> Symbiont early investors include [[Duncan Niederauer]], former CEO of the [[New York Stock Exchange]], and former co-head of [[Citadel LLC|Citadel]] Matt Andresen.<ref name=\"us-tech-company\" /><ref name=\"ex-nyse\">{{cite news|last=Bullock|first=Nicole|title=Ex-NYSE head among trading veterans backing blockchain start-up|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/0823a136-0ead-11e5-9ae0-00144feabdc0.html|date=2015-06-09|newspaper=Financial Times|accessdate=2016-06-01}}</ref>  In January 2019,  [[Nasdaq|Nasdaq Ventures]] led a US$20 million [[Series B]] round. [[Citigroup]], [[Mike Novogratz]]\u2019s crypto-focus merchant bank, Galaxy Digital Holdings Ltd. and Raptor Group Holdings also participated in the round.<ref name=\"novogratz\" /> Symbiont has 75 employees as of June 2019.<ref name=\"trillion\" />\n\n==Products and customers==\nSymbiont's blockchain products manage the life cycle of financial instruments including mortgages, private equity, syndicated loans and market data.<ref name=trillion />\n\nIn December 2017, Vanguard announced a pilot program with Symbiont to build a product for managing [[Stock market index|index data]] on its blockchain platform.<ref name=\"eha\">{{cite web|last=Eha|first=Brian Patrick|title=Vanguard leapfrogs cautious banks, unveils blockchain network plan|url=https://www.americanbanker.com/news/vanguard-mutual-fund-giant-plans-blockchain-network|date=2017-12-12|website=American Banker|accessdate=2017-12-14}}</ref> Vanguard now uses Symbiont blockchain technology in production to manage US$1.5 trillion of [[index funds]],<ref name=blockchain50>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/michaeldelcastillo/2020/02/19/blockchain-50/#303c8c787553|title=Blockchain 50|last1=del Castillo|first1=Michael|last2=Schifrin|first2=Matt|website=Forbes|access-date=2020-02-19|date=2020-02-19}}</ref> where Symbiont's technology eliminates manual reconciliation between Vanguard and the [[Center for Research in Security Prices]] (CRSP), who publishes data to the blockchain network.<ref name=nasdaq /> This was the first production integration of blockchain technology by a major financial institution into one of their core systems.<ref name=\"trillion\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeffkauflin/2019/05/30/vanguard-is-now-using-blockchain-technology-to-help-manage-13-trillion-in-index-funds/|title=Vanguard Is Now Using Blockchain Technology To Help Manage $1.3 Trillion In Index Funds|last=Kauflin|first=Jeff|date=2019-05-30|website=Forbes|access-date=2019-06-28}}</ref>\n\nSymbiont's technology also powers a venture by Vanguard aiming at making peer-to-peer trading between [[asset management|asset managers]] in the [[foreign exchange market]] possible for the first time.<ref name=marsh2>{{cite news|newspaper=Bloomberg|last=Marsh|first=Alastair|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-10-03/vanguard-to-challenge-banks-grip-on-6-trillion-currency-market|date=2019-10-03|accessdate=2019-10-24|title=Vanguard to Challenge Banks\u2019 Grip on $6 Trillion Currency Market}}</ref> The Assembly [[Investment banking|FICC]] network allows for the decentralized [[collateral management]] among asset managers trading in foreign exchange while mitigating [[counterparty risk]].<ref name=profit-and-loss />\n\n<!--\n==Technology==\nEach market participant runs its own node in a given network, and a shared log is replicated across all nodes identically, but each firm can only decrypt transactions that it is a participant in.<ref name=profit-and-loss />\n-->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://symbiont.io/}}\n* [http://synapsloans.io Synaps Loans website]\n\n[[Category:Blockchain entities]]\n[[Category:Companies based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Financial technology companies]]\n[[Category:Financial software companies]]\n[[Category:2015 establishments in New York City]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 2015]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2015]]\n", "name_user": "Moontreasure", "label": "safe", "comment": "tweak wording and whitespace", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symbiont_(company)"}
